uses_data:
The collected data in this study includes ultrastructural measurements of cuticle layers thicknesses from the fossil plant Baiera furcata. This is the first dataset of its kind for this species, and it provides a suitable number of measurements among fossil records. Baiera furcata is a member of the Ginkgoales order, which is a widespread Mesozoic fossil group. The dataset also includes ultrastructural data on the fine details of layers of cuticles within Ginkgoales, which is still poorly documented. The dataset is related to an increasing number of fine details studies in this order, which may bring new insights in various topics such as taxonomy, palaeoenvironment, and evolution. 

In addition to the measurements of cuticle layers thicknesses, the dataset also includes EDS (Energy-Dispersive X-ray Spectroscopy) element analysis of the fossil cuticles. This is a new topic with limited data, but Ginkgoales are becoming more and more present in these studies. The EDS element analysis provides new insights in taxonomy, palaeoenvironment, and evolution. The dataset also includes EDS element analysis of cell remnants of Baiera furcata, which is a valuable addition to the knowledge and understanding of plant cells.

The dataset is presented in three supplementary materials. Appendix A contains the raw measurements of the cuticle layers thicknesses for Baiera furcata, with 30 values for each of the two layers (A2 and B1) among four types of cuticles observed. Appendix B contains the results of the EDS element analysis for the two taxa Baiera furcata and Sphenobaiera huangii, including the detection of ten elements and their detailed analysis. Appendix C contains the EDS element analysis of cell remnants of Baiera furcata.

Overall, this dataset provides valuable information on the ultrastructural details of cuticle layers thicknesses in Baiera furcata and contributes to the understanding of plant cuticles and plant cells.
collection_explanation: The dataset was collected by obtaining fossil cuticles from Baiera furcata. The samples were treated with various chemicals and selected leaves were embedded in Epon resin. Thin sections (1 μm) and ultrathin sections (60-70 nm) were then cut from the embedded leaves using a diamond knife. The ultrathin sections were mounted on copper grids, and two sets of sections were obtained. One set was stained and observed with a transmission electron microscope, while the other set remained unstained for Energy Dispersive Spectroscopy (EDS) analysis performed with the same TEM. The same technique was used for the EDS data for Sphenobaiera huangii cuticles, as described in a separate research article by Wang et al. The CRediT author statement indicates that Gaëtan Guignard and Xiao-Ju Yang were involved in the conceptualization, methodology, data curation, and investigation of the dataset, while Yong-Dong Wang was involved in the writing, reviewing, and editing. The value of the dataset lies in its contribution to the understanding of cuticle layers thicknesses in Baiera furcata, a member of the Ginkgoales order. This is the first ultrastructural data on cuticle layers thicknesses from this locality in East Inner Mongolia, and it provides a suitable number of measurements among fossil records. The dataset also contributes to the study of fine details of cuticle layers within Ginkgoales, which is still poorly documented. The dataset has potential for future studies and comparisons, and it may provide new insights in various topics such as taxonomy, palaeoenvironment, and evolution. The EDS elements analysis of fossil cuticles is a new topic with limited data, but Ginkgoales are increasingly being studied in this context and may provide valuable information for further understanding of plant cells.

collection_sources: The data has been collected from Baiera furcata and Sphenobaiera huangii.
collection_infrastructure:
The tools, devices, and infrastructure used during the collection process include:

1. Transmission Electron Microscope (TEM): Used to observe and photograph the ultrathin sections of the fossil cuticles.
2. Copper grids: Used to mount the ultrathin sections for observation under the TEM.
3. Energy Dispersive Spectroscopy (EDS) analysis: Performed on the TEM using SIRIUS SD ENSOTECH and IDFIX software to analyze the elemental composition of the fossil cuticles.
4. Epon resin: Used for embedding the fossil cuticles and preparing the blocks for cutting.
5. Diamond knife: Used to cut thin sections (1 μm) and ultrathin sections (60-70 nm) of the embedded fossil cuticles.
6. Uranyl acetate and lead citrate: Used to stain the ultrathin sections for better contrast and visibility under the TEM.
7. Nanjing Institute of Geology and Palaeontology, Chinese Academy of Sciences: Housed the hand specimen of Baiera furcata.
8. Lyon-1 University, Villeurbanne, France: Stored the TEM and EDS material, as well as the negatives.
annotation_explanation: The annotation process done over the data involves the identification and categorization of different components and measurements within the data. This includes the identification of different layers of the cuticle (CP, CL, A1, A2, B1, B2), the measurement of thicknesses of these layers, and the analysis of EDS elements within the cuticles and cell remnants. The data is organized into three supplementary materials (Appendices A, B, and C) which contain the raw measurements and analysis results for the different components. The annotation process likely involved extracting and recording the relevant measurements and analysis results from the data.

uses_uses:
The recommended uses of the dataset are: 
1. Characterization of bone marrow stem cells (BMSCs) and their pluripotency and stem cell-specific surface markers.
2. Analysis of cellular penetration into the PEG-PU polymer network and the mechanism via enzymatic activation of MMP-2 and MMP-13.
3. Comparison of various routes of transplantation-mediated BMSCs engraftment in a murine model using bone marrow transplantation chimeras.
4. Evaluation of the accelerated wound healing capacity of BMSCs when transplanted using polymer networks as scaffolds.
5. Histological analysis of wound tissue to assess the effects of BMSCs and the polymer network on tissue repair.
6. Immunostaining analyses of wound tissue sections to evaluate the engraftment of transplanted BMSCs.

uses_represents_people: No. The data of the dataset does not represent people. The dataset contains information about gene expression, surface proteins, cell penetrability, wound healing, and histopathological analysis.
uses_collected_from_people: No, the subjects of the collection process are not humans. The data was collected using various instruments and techniques, and the figures in the document show the characterization and analysis of mouse BMSCs and wound tissue in mice.
uses_data:
The collected data in this study includes various types of information and measurements related to the evaluation of biomaterials as cell delivery vehicles for tissue engineering and regenerative medicine. The data was acquired using several instruments and techniques, including DSC Q200 and TG Q50 TA Instruments for thermal analysis, flow cytometer Beckman Coulter MoFlo Legacy for cell analysis, confocal and fluorescence microscopes for imaging, and a thermal cycler Takara TP600 and applied biosystems 7900HT real-time PCR for gene expression analysis.

The data is provided in both raw and analyzed formats, allowing for further analysis and interpretation. The experimental factors in this study include the excisional splinting wound model and cell transplantation chimeras, which were used to investigate the site-specific homing and engraftment of transplanted stem cell chimeras using different routes of administration.

The figures in the document provide visual representations of the data. Figure 1 shows the characterization of mouse BMSCs, including the expression of pluripotency and stem cell marker genes, as well as the differential expression of surface proteins. Figure 2 demonstrates cell penetrability in the polymer network, while Figure 3 shows collagen zymography indicating cell penetrability. Figure 4 displays the effect of bone marrow stem cells-polymer network on wound healing, and Figure 5 presents histopathological analysis of wound tissue healing in the presence of BMSC-polymer network. Figure 7 shows BMSC engraftment at the wound site.

Overall, the collected data provides valuable insights into the penetration mechanism of cells into biomaterials and the site-specific homing and engraftment of transplanted stem cell chimeras. It can be used by the research community to further investigate and evaluate biomaterials for tissue engineering and regenerative medicine applications.
collection_explanation:
The dataset was collected through a combination of image analysis, cell isolation, DNA extraction, and real-time PCR. 

For image analysis, the image files were opened using ImageJ software and converted to 16-bit. The staining in the images was quantified by adjusting the threshold using various steps provided in the software. The selected gray level measurements were quantified using the "Analyze - Measure" option, and the results were saved in a table format. Graphs were created by transferring this data to an Excel file. Additionally, the "Analyze - Analyze Particles" option was used to measure individual feature profiles.

For cell isolation, bone marrow stem cells (BMSCs) were isolated from male C57BL/6J mice and transplanted to female C57BL/6J mice through various routes of administration. The BMSCs were cultured along with PEG-PU before implantation on the wound. After 7 days post-surgery, wound tissue and other tissues/organs were harvested and ground in liquid nitrogen. DNA was isolated from the tissue using NucleoSpin tissue kit.

Real-time PCR was performed to analyze the expression of the Y-linked zinc finger protein (Zfy-1) gene, with Bcl-2 used as a reference control. A standard curve for the engraftment of male cells was plotted by increasing the percentage of male BMSC DNA with female BMSC DNA.

In addition to image analysis and cell isolation, various instruments and techniques were used to acquire data for the dataset. These include DSC Q200 and TG Q50 TA Instruments for thermal analysis, flow cytometer Beckman Coulter MoFlo Legacy for cell analysis, confocal and fluorescence microscopes for imaging, and a thermal cycler Takara TP600 and applied biosystems 7900HT real-time PCR for PCR analysis.

The data format of the dataset is raw and analyzed, and the experimental factors include the excisional splinting wound model and cell transplantation chimeras. The experimental features include the characterization of mouse BMSCs, cell penetrability in the polymer network, bone marrow stem cell-polymer network-mediated wound healing, and histopathological analysis of wound tissue healing in the presence of BMSC-polymer network.

annotation_explanation: The annotation process for the data involved several steps. First, the image files were opened using ImageJ software and converted to 16-bit. Then, the staining was quantified by adjusting the threshold using the "Image -Adjust -Threshold" function. Background subtraction and binary watershed processing were applied using the appropriate functions. The measurements were set using the "Analyze -Set Measurements" options, and only the selected gray level measurements were quantified using the "Limit to Threshold" option. The results appeared in a table form and were saved. Graphs were created by transferring the data to an Excel file. Individual feature profiles were measured using the "Analyze -Analyze Particles" function. Intensity measurements were performed within regions of interest by choosing the parameters at a specific step.

uses_data:
The collected data consists of kinetic data from enzyme stability assays and enzyme kinetics experiments. The data is organized in folders and files within the DYNAFIT software. The folder "Enzyme kinetics data" contains subfolders for different experiments, each containing ".txt" files with data from kinetic experiments. 

For example, the folder "data_AARCAp_varying_AcAcCoA_NADH" contains the file "data.txt" which contains initial rates of reactions catalyzed by AAR CAp at different concentrations of acetoacetyl-CoA, with a fixed NADH concentration of 300 μM. The data in this file is arranged in two columns, with the first column representing the acetoacetyl-CoA concentrations in micromolar and the second column representing the measured initial rates in micromol of product/micromol of enzyme/second.

In addition to the kinetic data, there are also reaction progress curves reported in separate ".txt" files within the other five data folders. These files contain data arranged in two columns, with the first column representing time in seconds and the second column representing the varying substrate/cofactor concentration in micromolar.

To analyze the data, the DYNAFIT software needs to be downloaded and activated. The DYNAFIT scripts contain lines indicating the route to the data-containing folder, usually written with reference to the folder where DYNAFIT is installed.
collection_explanation: The dataset was collected using spectrophotometry in a plate reader equipped with a monochromator and temperature control. The data was recorded at 30 °C. Continuous cell cultures were also studied at 37 °C. The data from continuous cultures were obtained by integrating data obtained by different means. The data collection process was controlled by the user through the software Gen5.

collection_sources: The data has been collected from spectrophotometry, plate reader, Gen5 software, and continuous cultures.

annotation_explanation:
The annotation process done over the data involves organizing and labeling the data files and folders in a specific structure. In the DYNAFIT script, the data is declared using the [ data ] keyword, and the location of the data files is specified using the directory keyword. The extension of the data files is indicated using the extension keyword. The independent variable is identified using a variable keyword, and the name of the data file is specified using the file data keyword.

The results of the analysis are declared using the [ output ] keyword, and the location of the output folder is specified using the directory keyword. The Response or molar Response, which is a proportionality constant to express the output parameters in convenient units, is also mentioned in the script.

The data is organized in folders based on different enzyme stability assays and kinetic experiments. Each experiment has a separate folder containing the data file. The data file contains the initial rates of reactions arranged in two columns, with the first column representing the concentrations of the substrate and the second column representing the measured initial rates.

DYNAFIT is used for analyzing the kinetic data and finding the best-fitted values for the parameters of a given model. It also allows for comparing different models to determine the best explanation for the observed results. The user needs to provide a (bio)chemical mechanism representing the interactions, and the rate constants characterizing the elemental interactions are specified in the DYNAFIT code. Comments in the code are indicated using the semicolon (;).

uses_data:
The collected data in this study provides valuable information for computationally efficient modeling of powder bed fusion. The data focuses on the elimination of powder elements from the finite element model, specifically in relation to cooling rates for solid parts in powder bed fusion with varying powder throughthicknesses. The cooling rates presented in the data are important for understanding heat transfer mechanisms in powder bed fusion and can be beneficial for additive manufacturing part designers, build layout designers, and equipment operators.

The data includes cooling rates for multiple computational heat transfer models, which can be used as a reference for informing powder bed fusion build experiments on appropriate data sampling for heat transfer measurements. This information is crucial for optimizing the additive manufacturing process and improving the quality of the final products.

The authors would like to acknowledge the Irish Centre for High-End Computing (ICHEC) for providing simulation conditions and the SDI. The research has been funded by the Irish Research Council, the Government of Ireland Postgraduate Programme, the Hardiman Research Scholarship, the College of Engineering and Informatics of NUI Galway Scholarship, and a research grant from Science Foundation Ireland (SFI) that is co-funded under the European Regional Development Fund.

Figure 1 in the document shows the part-powder thermal loss, including the verification of Ti6Al4V powder in plane depth during part-powder conduction and the cooling curves of part-powder conduction and powder-interface convection. Table 1 of the document provides additional information on the resolution, energy, and time dependency on layer scaling in finite element modeling of laser beam powder bed fusion additive manufacturing.

Overall, the collected data in this study contributes to a computationally efficient approximation of part-powder conduction as surface free convection in powder bed fusion process modeling. The data is valuable for understanding heat transfer mechanisms and optimizing the additive manufacturing process.
collection_explanation:
The dataset was collected through a simulation process. The authors used a finite element model to simulate a single layer consisting of a solid region and a powder region. The solid region was exposed to a heat flux, while the powder region experienced heating due to conduction from the solid part only. The temperature at the interface between the solid part and the powder was monitored for a range of powder in-plane depths. 

To approximate the part-powder conduction as surface free convection, a new model was prepared with the powder removed. Convection at the part surface (formerly the powder-part interface) was defined, and the convection coefficient was calibrated to produce the same cooling profile as the converged cooling profile from previous simulations. 

The material properties for the Ti6Al4V powder were assumed to be related to the solid material properties via powder bulk porosity. A porosity of 40.5% was determined based on published powder and solid densities. The thermal conductivity of the powder was assumed to be equal to the solid above the melt point, and the specific heat of the powder was considered to be equal to the solid properties. 

During the cooling step, active layer convection and radiation occurred at the top surface of the active layer. The surface heat loss due to convection was calculated using Newton's law of cooling, with the heat transfer coefficient of convection, surface temperature, and chamber temperature as parameters. The chamber temperature was set to 293 K, which was the same as the initial temperature of the powder and the characteristic heat transfer.

uses_data:
The collected data in this study includes the draft genome sequence of Bacillus sp. strain MHSD28, a bacterial endophyte isolated from Dicoma anomala. The genome sequence data was uploaded on the Type Strain Genome Server (TYGS) for taxonomic analysis with other validly published type strains. The average nucleotide identity with closely related species was determined using the Orthologous Average Nucleotide Identity Software Tool (OAT).

The draft genome of Bacillus sp. strain MHSD28 has a total length of 5,571,729 base pairs (bp) and is composed of 43 contigs. The largest contig is 1,785,042 bp in length, with an N50 value of 1,474,247 bp. The G+C content of the genome is 35.23%, which is within the range typically observed for Bacillus species.

The whole genome sequencing of Bacillus sp. strain MHSD28 was performed using the Illumina MiSeq platform at the Agricultural Research Council (ARC) in Onderstepoort, South Africa. The genome assembly was conducted using the de novo assembly tool Unicycler, and the assembly quality was assessed using Quast.

The genome assembly was then annotated through the NCBI PGAAP (Prokaryotic Genome Annotation Pipeline). Pre-annotation analysis of the raw sequence data was performed using FastQC. Overall, the collected data provides information on the genome sequence, assembly, and annotation of Bacillus sp. strain MHSD28.
collection_explanation: The dataset was collected through a series of steps. First, the raw sequence data was assessed for quality using FastQC. Then, de novo assembly of the genome was performed using Unicycler. The resulting assembly was evaluated using Quast. The final step in the collection process was the annotation of the genome, which was done through the NCBI PGAAP. Additionally, the genome sequence data was uploaded to the Type Strain Genome Server (TYGS) for taxonomic analysis with other type strains. The average nucleotide identity with closely related species was determined using the Orthologous Average Nucleotide Identity Software Tool (OAT). The genome statistics of Bacillus sp. strain MHSD28, including its size, number of contigs, largest contig size, N50 value, and G+C content, are provided in Table 1 of the document. The whole genome sequencing of Bacillus sp. strain MHSD28 was performed using the Illumina MiSeq platform at the Agricultural Research Council (ARC) in Onderstepoort, South Africa.

- Quast (version 0.4.6.3) for assessing the assembly
- NCBI PGAAP for genome annotation
- Illumina MiSeq platform for whole genome sequencing
- Agricultural Research Council (ARC), Onderstepoort, South Africa for sequencing
- Type Strain Genome Server (TYGS) (https://tygs.dsmz.de) for genome-based taxonomic analysis
- Orthologous Average Nucleotide Identity Software Tool (OAT) for determining average nucleotide identity with closely related species.
annotation_explanation: The annotation process for the genome assembly of Bacillus sp. strain MHSD28 was performed through the NCBI PGAAP (Prokaryotic Genome Annotation Pipeline). This pipeline is a web-based tool provided by the National Center for Biotechnology Information (NCBI) that automatically annotates bacterial and archaeal genomes. The resulting draft genome of Bacillus sp. strain MHSD28 had a size of 5,571,729 bp, with 43 contigs. The annotation process likely involved the identification and annotation of genes, coding sequences, regulatory elements, and other genomic features within the genome sequence.

uses_uses:
The recommended uses of the dataset are: 
1. Experimental design and data analysis related to biochar fabrication and lake water treatment.
2. Characterization of biomass and tailored biochars using BET, TGA, and EDX.
3. Study of NOM adsorption and desorption using alkaline solutions.
4. Illustrations and visual aids for readers of the related article.
uses_ml_approach: No, there is no mention about any test using a machine learning approach.
uses_data_limits: No, there is no mention about non-recommended uses or generalization limits of the data.
uses_represents_people: No. The data of the dataset does not represent people.
uses_collected_from_people: No. The subjects of the collection process are not humans. The dataset includes measurements and analyses related to the tailoring of biochars from pinecone biomass for the adsorption of natural organic matter from lake water.
uses_data:
The collected data in this dataset includes various measurements and analyses related to the tailoring of biochars from pinecone biomass for the adsorption of natural organic matter (NOM) from lake water. The data includes schematics, figures, and tables.

The dataset provides information on the characterization of the biomass and tailored biochars using techniques such as Brunauer, Emmett and Teller surface area measurement (BET), thermogravimetric analysis (TGA), and energy dispersive X-ray (EDX). This characterization data helps in understanding the properties of the biochars and biomass.

Additionally, the dataset includes data on the adsorption of NOM from lake water by the tailored biochars, as well as the desorption of NOM using alkaline solutions. This information is important for studying the effectiveness of the tailored biochars in removing NOM from water.

The dataset also includes information on the reabsorption kinetics of NOM by the regenerated biochar from the lake water. This data helps in understanding the potential for reusing the biochar for NOM removal.

Overall, this dataset complements the experimental design and data gathered for the article on biochar fabrication and lake water treatment. It provides valuable information on the steps involved in tailoring biochar, characterization data for the biochars and biomass, NOM adsorption and desorption data, and NOM reabsorption kinetics. The figures and tables in the dataset further illustrate the findings of the article.
collection_explanation:
The dataset was collected for the purpose of tailoring biochars from pinecone biomass for the adsorption of natural organic matter (NOM) from lake water. The collection process involved several steps and techniques. 

First, lake water samples were collected from Lake Pitkäjärvi in Espoo, Finland. The concentration of NOM in the water was determined using UV absorbance measurement on a UV-1201 Shimadzu-spectrophotometer at a wavelength of 254 nm.

The materials used in the study were characterized using various techniques. The Brunauer, Emmett and Teller (BET) surface area measurement was performed using a Tristar II-Micromeritics instrument. Thermogravimetric analysis (TGA) was conducted using a TGA Q500 instrument from TA Instruments. Energy dispersive X-ray (EDX) analysis was carried out using a JEOL JSM-7500FA analytical field emission scanning electron microscope.

Adsorption and desorption batch experiments were conducted on a shaker at room temperature with a speed of 150 rpm. The adsorption experiments involved the use of tailored biochars and lake water, while the desorption experiments used an alkaline solution.

The dataset includes schematics, figures, and tables that provide information on the steps involved in tailoring biochars from pinecone biomass, the characterization of the materials, and the adsorption and desorption of NOM from lake water.

This dataset is complementary to the experimental setup and data presented in the article referenced as [1] on biochar fabrication and lake water treatment.

uses_data:
The collected data in this study includes various tables and figures that provide information on the mechanical properties of different types of wine stoppers. 

Tables 1 and 2 present the different formulations of the micro-agglomerated cork stopper groups that were tested, as well as the dimensions and density for each cork stopper type, respectively. 

Figure 1 depicts the device that was developed in the INIA-CIFOR Cork Laboratory for measuring the displacement force. 

Figures 2 and 3 display the maximum compression force distributions and the Young's modulus distributions per stopper type, respectively. 

Figure 4 shows the reaction force distributions for each stopper type. 

Figure 5 illustrates the diameter recovery after compression test and after specific time intervals (15, 60, and 1,440 minutes) for each stopper type. 

Lastly, Figure 6 presents the displacement force distributions per stopper type. 

In Figures 2-6, the boxplot notches indicate a 95% confidence interval on the median. 

Overall, this dataset provides comprehensive information on the mechanical properties of different types of wine stoppers, including micro-agglomerated cork, natural cork, and synthetic stoppers.
collection_explanation: The dataset was collected in the INIA-CIFOR Cork Laboratory. The different formulation of the micro-agglomerated cork stopper groups were tested and the dimensions and density for each cork stopper type were recorded in Tables 1 and 2, respectively. The displacement force was measured using a device developed in the laboratory, as shown in Fig. 1. The maximum compression force distributions, Young's modulus distributions, and reaction force distributions for each stopper type were also recorded, as shown in Figs. 2-4. The diameter recovery after compression test and at different time intervals (15, 60, and 1,440 min) for each stopper type was measured and recorded in Fig. 5. Finally, the displacement force distributions per stopper type were also recorded, as shown in Fig. 6. The boxplot notches in Figs. 2-6 indicate a 95% confidence interval on the median.

uses_data:
The collected data in this study consists of electrochemical data for various polypyridine complexes of Ru(II). The data is presented in several tables in the document. 

Table 2 provides electrochemical data for Tris(4,4'-dimethyl-2,2'-bipyridine)ruthenium bis(tetrafluoroborate) complex. The data includes the potential in volts (V) versus ferrocene (FcH) for the Ru(II/III) redox couple in acetonitrile (CH3CN) at different scan rates.

Table 3 presents electrochemical data for Tris(4,4'-dimethoxy-2,2'-bipyridine)ruthenium bis(tetrafluoroborate) complex. Similar to Table 2, it includes the potential in V versus FcH for the Ru(II/III) redox couple in acetonitrile at different scan rates.

Table 4 provides electrochemical data for Tris(4,4'-di-tert-butyl-2,2'-bipyridine)ruthenium bis(tetrafluoroborate) complex. Again, it includes the potential in V versus FcH for the Ru(II/III) redox couple in acetonitrile at different scan rates.

Table 5 presents electrochemical data for Tris(4,4'-diamino-2,2'-bipyridine)ruthenium bis(tetrafluoroborate) complex, as well as Tris(2,2'-bipyridine)ruthenium bis(tetrafluoroborate) complex. The data includes the potential in V versus FcH for the Ru(II/III) redox couple in acetonitrile at different scan rates.

Table 7 and Table 8 do not provide any specific information about the electrochemical data.

Table 9 provides electrochemical data for Tris(5-chloro-1,10-phenanthroline)ruthenium bis(tetrafluoroborate) complex. The data includes the potential in V versus FcH for the Ru(II/III) redox couple in acetonitrile at different scan rates.

Table 13 provides electrochemical data for Tris(1,10-phenanthroline)ruthenium bis(tetrafluoroborate) complex. Similar to the previous tables, it includes the potential in V versus FcH for the Ru(II/III) redox couple in acetonitrile at different scan rates.

Overall, the collected data consists of electrochemical measurements of the Ru(II/III) redox couple in acetonitrile for various polypyridine complexes of Ru(II). The data includes the potential in V versus FcH at different scan rates for each complex.
collection_explanation: The dataset was collected through an experimental process. The researchers synthesized samples for their study. They used acetonitrile as the solvent-electrolyte solution in the electrochemical cell. Before starting the experiment, they degassed the solvent-electrolyte solution by bubbling argon gas (Ar(g)) through it for approximately 10 minutes. Then, they added the synthesized samples to the acetonitrile-electrolyte solution and degassed it again for approximately 3 minutes. Throughout the electrochemical analysis, they maintained a blanket of argon gas in the cell. The specific details of the electrochemical analysis and measurements are not provided in the given context.

uses_uses:
The recommended uses of the dataset are: 
1. Further development of processes used to infer the immunoglobulin gene repertoire of an individual and interpretation of the results of such analyses.
2. Further development of processes used to infer new germline gene sequences.
3. Identification of unrecognized alleles of immunoglobulin germline genes.
4. Interpretation of sequence diversity in the ascending strand of CDR3 of naïve and antigen-specific immune repertoires.
5. Analysis of nucleotide composition in CDR3 codons encoded by IGHV germline gene.
uses_ml_approach: No, there is no mention about any test using a machine learning approach.
uses_data_limits: No, there is no mention about non-recommended uses or generalization limits of the data.
uses_represents_people: No. The data of the dataset represents sequences of immunoglobulin genes, not people.
uses_collected_from_people: No. The subjects of the collection process are not humans. The data set consists of FASTQ raw data files generated in the laboratory and transcripts from peripheral blood memory B cells.
uses_data:
The collected data in this study consists of FASTQ raw data files generated in the laboratory. These files were processed using pRESTO 0.4.4 and pRESTO 0.5.4 software. The sequences in the files were filtered, trimmed, paired, assembled, and divided into isotype-specific FASTA files. Isotype annotation was confirmed by evaluating the presence of isotype-specific sequences, and any sequences lacking such were discarded. Germline genes were inferred for IgM encoding sequences using IgDiscover software, with germline gene libraries retrieved from IMGT. The IGHV library was adjusted to cover a specific codon range. The sequences were further filtered to include only those that encoded at least eight amino acids in the CDR3, covered at least 99% of the inferred IGHV germline gene, and lacked errors compared to the inferred IGHV gene.

In addition to the main data set, an unrelated set of raw sequence data was downloaded from the European Nucleotide Archive. These data contained transcripts from peripheral blood memory B cells and were processed similarly to the main data set, but without dividing the sequences based on isotype. Germline genes were inferred using IMGT HighV-QUEST software.

The collected data is valuable for the development of processes used to infer the immunoglobulin gene repertoire of an individual and for interpreting the results of such analyses. It is also useful for identifying unrecognized alleles of immunoglobulin germline genes and for interpreting sequence diversity in the CDR3 of naïve and antigen-specific immune repertoires.
collection_explanation:
The dataset was collected by processing FASTQ raw data files generated in the laboratory. These raw data files were obtained from the European Nucleotide Archive with accession number PRJEB18926. The sequences in the raw data files were filtered, trimmed, paired, assembled, and divided into isotype-specific FASTA files using the pRESTO 0.4.4 software. Isotype annotation was confirmed by evaluating the presence of isotype-specific sequences, and any sequences lacking such were discarded. Germline genes for IgM encoding sequences were inferred using the IgDiscover software, with germline gene libraries retrieved from IMGT. The IGHV library was adjusted to cover codon 25-105. The sequences were then filtered to include only those that encoded at least eight amino acids in the CDR3, covered at least 99% of the inferred IGHV germline gene, and lacked errors compared with the inferred IGHV gene.

In addition to the main data set, an unrelated set of raw sequence data was downloaded from the European Nucleotide Archive with accession numbers SRX709625, SRX709626, and SRX709627. These data contained transcripts from peripheral blood memory B cells encoding paired H chain V domain and light chain V domain in three subjects. The processing steps for this data set were similar to the main data set, but pRESTO 0.5.4 was used instead of pRESTO 0.4.4. Since the isotype encoded by the transcripts was unknown, no dividing of sequences based on isotype was performed. Duplicate sequences were removed using the CollapseSeq tool in pRESTO 0.5.4, and IGHV genes were inferred using IMGT HighV-QUEST. For further analysis, only sequences inferred as productive to one single allele of an IGHV gene and that had at least eight amino acids in the CDR3 were used.

The samples for the dataset were collected from peripheral blood and bone marrow of six allergic subjects. The collection of samples was approved by the regional ethical review board at Lund University. Mononuclear cells were isolated from the samples, and RNA was extracted from duplicate samples. cDNA was produced from the RNA and amplified using Biomed2 primers targeting sequences encoding the constant domain and the first framework region of antibody H chains. The products were barcoded and sequenced using MiSeq technology with a paired-end setting (2 × 300 bp) at the National Genomics Infrastructure.

The dataset also includes an analysis of the nucleotide composition in the CDR3 codons encoded by IGHV germline genes. This analysis was performed separately for each donor in both the main and unrelated data sets. Transcripts originating from 47 different alleles of IGHV genes were studied, with each allele having at least 500 transcripts in at least three donors in the main data set. The mean frequency of nucleotide bases at each examined position was calculated for both data sets. The analysis was limited to subjects with at least 500 transcripts originating from a certain allele of an IGHV gene in the main data set, and 250 transcripts in the unrelated data set. The results of this analysis are summarized in Table 1. Additionally, the nucleotide composition was analyzed at position 108 for transcripts originating from four specific germline genes/alleles.

annotation_explanation:
The annotation process done over the data involved several steps. 

First, the FASTQ raw data files were processed using pRESTO 0.4.4 to filter, trim, pair, assemble, and divide the sequences into isotype-specific FASTA files. Isotype annotation was confirmed by evaluating the presence of isotype-specific sequences, and any sequences lacking such were discarded.

Next, germline genes were inferred for IgM encoding sequences using IgDiscover. Germline gene libraries retrieved from IMGT were used, with the IGHV library adjusted to cover codon 25-105. Sequences were then filtered to include only those that encoded at least eight amino acids in the CDR3, covered at least 99% of the inferred IGHV germline gene, and lacked errors compared with the inferred IGHV gene.

For an unrelated set of raw sequence data, duplicate sequences were removed using the pRESTO 0.5.4 CollapseSeq tool, and IGHV genes were inferred using IMGT HighV-QUEST. Only sequences inferred as productive to one single allele of an IGHV gene and that had at least eight amino acids in the CDR3 were used for further analysis.

Overall, the annotation process involved filtering, trimming, pairing, assembling, dividing, confirming isotype annotation, inferring germline genes, and filtering for specific criteria in order to analyze the data.

uses_data:
The collected data in this study consists of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) spectra of meroterpenoids from the roots of Arnfebia euchroma. The NMR spectra were recorded using a Bruker DPX-400 spectrometer and standard Bruker pulse programs. The chemical shifts in the spectra were shown as d-values with reference to tetramethylsilane (TMS) as an internal standard. 

The NMR spectra include both 1H-NMR and 13C-NMR spectra. Figure 1 shows the 1H-NMR spectrum of meroterpenoid 2, while Figure 3 shows the 1H-NMR spectrum of meroterpenoid 5. Figure 2, Figure 4, Figure 5, Figure 6, Figure 7, and Figure 9 collectively show the 13C-NMR spectrum of meroterpenoid 2. Figure 8 shows the 13C-NMR spectrum of meroterpenoid 7, and Figure 11 shows the 1H-NMR spectrum of meroterpenoid 9.

The samples used for the NMR analysis were isolated from the dichloromethane fraction of the roots of Arnfebia euchroma extracts. The samples were dissolved in either DMSO-d6 or CD3Cl before the NMR tests.

The data was collected at the herbarium of the Key Laboratory for New Drug Research of TCM, Research Institute of Tsinghua University in Shenzhen, China. The data is accessible and can be found in the transparency document associated with this article, which is available online.

The NMR data of meroterpenoids is valuable for elucidating their chemical structures and analogues. This information allows for comparisons across different meroterpenoids from algal species or other natural sources.
collection_explanation: The dataset was collected by isolating the roots of Arnfebia euchroma, which were purchased in Haozhou city, Anhui Province, China. The roots were then extracted using dichloromethane, and the resulting sample was dissolved in either DMSO-d6 or CD3Cl before undergoing NMR testing. The NMR spectra data of meroterpenoids were recorded using a Bruker DPX-400 spectrometer with standard Bruker pulse programs. The chemical shifts were shown as d-values with reference to tetramethylsilane (TMS) as an internal standard. The data was collected at the herbarium of Key Laboratory for New Drug Research of TCM, Research institute of Tsinghua University in Shenzhen, Shenzhen, China. The dataset includes NMR data for six previously undescribed naturally occurring meroterpenoids (2, 5-9) and seven known meroterpenoids (1, 3, 4, 10-13) isolated from the roots of Arnebia euchroma. The NMR data of meroterpenoids 1-5 and 8 suggest they are structural analogues containing a bridgehead double bond.

collection_explanation:
The dataset was collected using a specific experimental design, materials, and methods. The process involved several steps. 

First, the tissue preparations were done by euthanizing mice using CO2 asphyxiation followed by cervical dislocation. The eyes were then enucleated and cryo-preserved in Tissue-Tek O.C.T compound. Cross sections of the mouse eyes, 10 μm thick, were cut on a cryostat and adhered to glass slides.

For imaging retinal autofluorescence, cryo-sections were fixed in 4% paraformaldehyde for 15 minutes, washed with 1 × PBS with 0.1% Tween-20, and sealed in Vectashield mounting medium at 4 °C in the dark overnight. Regular confocal images of autofluorescence were collected using a Nikon A1plus confocal microscope with a Plan Apo λ 100x oil objective lens and specific lasers and emission filter cubes. Z-stacks were acquired, and the most intense plane in the red channel was selected for inclusion in the figure.

Spectral imaging of retinal autofluorescence was also done using the same confocal microscope and objective lens, but with a 403.1 nm laser and a spectral detector divided into 32 channels.

For Cy5-PNA staining, retinal cryo-sections were air-dried, fixed in 4% paraformaldehyde, washed with 1 × PBS, stained with Cy5-PNA, washed again with 1 × PBS, and sealed in ProLong® Diamond antifade reagent. Control retinal cryo-sections were processed identically except for not adding Cy5-PNA during staining. Images were acquired using the same confocal microscope with specific lasers and emission filters.

For subunit C and IBA1 IHC-IF, retinal cryo-sections were air-dried, fixed in 4% paraformaldehyde, washed with 1 × PBS, permeabilized with Triton X-100, blocked with 1 × PBS supplemented with BSA and NGS, and incubated with corresponding primary antibodies. Images were acquired using the same confocal microscope with specific lasers.

Overall, the dataset collection process involved specific steps for tissue preparations, microscopy, and staining techniques, using a confocal microscope with specific settings and imaging parameters.

The data has been collected from the following sources or subjects: 
- Retinal cryo-sections
- Alexa Fluor Plus 647-labeled secondary antibody against rabbit IgG(H + L)
- Primary antibodies against Chx10 and subunit C
- Alexa Fluor 680-labeled secondary antibody against mouse IgG(H + L)
- Cy5-PNA staining
- DIC (differential interference contrast)
- Autofluorescence
- IBA1 (ionized calcium-binding adapter molecule 1)
collection_infrastructure: The tools, devices, and infrastructure used during the collection process include a cryostat for cutting cryo-sections of mouse eyes, glass slides for adhering the cryo-sections, a confocal microscope (Nikon A1plus) for imaging, a Plan Apo λ 100x oil objective lens for microscopy, lasers (403.1 nm, 487.9 nm, 561.4 nm, and 638.6 nm) for excitation, emission filter cubes (450/50 nm, 525/50 nm, 595/50 nm, and 700/75 nm) for detecting fluorescence, a spectral detector divided into 32 channels for spectral imaging, Vectashield mounting medium for sealing the cryo-sections, ProLong® Diamond antifade reagent for sealing and curing the cryo-sections, 4% paraformaldehyde for fixation, 1 × PBS with 0.1% Tween-20 for washing, Cy5-PNA for staining, Triton X-100 for permeabilization, BSA and NGS for blocking, and antibodies (Alexa Fluor Plus 647-labeled secondary antibody against rabbit IgG(H + L), anti-Chx10, Alexa Fluor 680-labeled secondary antibody against mouse IgG(H + L), anti-subunit C, and anti-IBA1) for immunostaining.
annotation_explanation: The annotation process done over the data involved several steps. First, confocal fluorescent microscopy was performed on retinal cryosections to visualize the distribution of the pathological autofluorescent lesions across all retina layers. Spectral imaging was then used to analyze the spectral properties of these lesions. Differential interference contrast microscopy was used to image the morphology of the lesions. Immunohistochemistry-immunofluorescence was performed to assess the colocalization of the lesions with mitochondrial ATP synthase F0 sub-complex subunit C, as well as with various established retinal cell type markers such as peanut agglutinin, ionized calcium binding adaptor molecule 1, and CHX10/Visual System Homeobox 2. The annotation process also involved the collection of autofluorescence using specific lasers and emission filters, as well as the staining of retinal cryosections with specific antibodies and lectins.

uses_uses:
The recommended uses of the dataset are: 
1. To provide reliable information on the energy and exergy efficiency of batch dryers used in various drying processes.
2. To examine the effect of particle size on exergy and exergy efficiency during drying processes.
3. To identify the sources and location of thermodynamic inefficiencies during the drying process and suggest areas for improvement.
4. To serve as a guide for selecting dryers for individuals and industries involved in food preservation.

uses_data:
The collected data in this study provides valuable information on the optimum temperature conditions for efficient energy usage during the drying of onion in a cabinet dryer. It also examines the effect of particle size on exergy and exergy efficiency during drying processes. 

The data allows us to identify the sources and locations of thermodynamic inefficiencies during the drying process and provides insights into potential areas for improvement. This information is particularly useful for individuals and industries involved in food preservation, as it can guide them in selecting the appropriate dryer for their specific needs.

The data is accessible within the article itself, and there is no related research article available. Additional transparency data associated with this study can be found in the online version of the article at the provided DOI link.
collection_explanation:
The dataset was collected through an experimental procedure. Fresh samples of onion fruits were purchased from a local market in Otta, Ogun state, Nigeria. The onions were washed with distilled water to remove any particles or contaminants that could affect the experimental results. 

The samples were then taken into a cabinet dryer at different thicknesses of 0.50 cm, 1.00 cm, and 1.50 cm. The drying process was conducted at different temperatures of 65°C, 75°C, 85°C, and 95°C. The weight loss of the samples at each temperature and thickness was determined using a digital weighing balance.

The data collected includes tables, figures, and images. The data format is raw and analyzed. The factors considered in the experiment include energy usage optimization in the drying process, which depends on various factors such as air temperature, feeding rates, relative humidity or wet-bulb depression, air velocity, air mass flow rate, and particle size, shape, and arrangement.

The dataset was collected by J Adewale Folayan, F N Osuolale, and P A L Anawe, and it focuses on the exergy and exergy analyses of the drying process of onion in a batch dryer. The data provides valuable information on the energy and exergy efficiency of batch dryers used in various drying processes, as well as the effect of particle size on exergy and exergy efficiency. The data can be used as a guide for dryer selection in food preservation for individuals and industries.

This includes examining the optimum temperature condition for efficient energy usage during the drying of onion in a cabinet dryer, as well as evaluating the energy and exergy efficiency of batch dryers used in various drying processes. The annotation process also involves studying the effect of particle size on exergy and exergy efficiency during drying processes. The goal of the annotation process is to identify sources and locations of thermodynamic inefficiencies during the drying process and determine potential areas for improvement. The annotated data can then serve as a guide for individuals and industries involved in food preservation when selecting a dryer.

The recommended uses of the dataset are: 
- Developing new approximate symmetry detection methods and performing comparison between these methods.
- Using the geometric data of trees and manually identified approximate symmetry planes as a reference data for approximate symmetry detection methods.
- Using the generated 3D tree models and tree skeleton in applications such as compression of tree models, instancing and decimation for visualization, radiative transfer modeling, and simulation of forest management and horticultural practices.
- Providing learning datasets for new machine learning applications, specifically for approximate symmetry detection and tree detection.

uses_data:
The collected data in this dataset includes 3D geometric data of leaf-off trees and manually specified parameters for each tree. The dataset is organized into 10 folders, each representing a different tree species. Each folder contains data for ten trees, which are numbered consecutively. The data for each tree is described in Table 1. The dataset also includes an MTL file, which contains material settings for visualizing the tree branches. An example of the dataset for one tree is shown in Figure 1. 

The trees in the dataset are approximately symmetric, with a manually identified predominant symmetry plane for each tree model. The parameters for procedural tree synthesis were manually adjusted to produce approximately bilaterally symmetric trees, which are grouped into species with distinct features. Each tree in the dataset has been manually annotated with an approximate symmetry plane. 

The dataset contains geometric data of branches, manually defined parameters for tree synthesis, point clouds, and a division plane with a score of bilateral symmetry strength. The generated trees can be used as benchmark data for verifying approximate reflectional symmetry detection methods. The 3D tree models can also be used for other applications, such as compression of tree models, instancing, decimation methods, and radiative transfer simulation and modeling. 

The 3D tree models were generated using the particle flow simulation method with manually defined parameters. The generated tree models were then annotated manually within the application. The 3D tree models were converted into LAS files using the CloudCompare application. 

The value of this dataset lies in its comprehensive comparison between approximate symmetry detection methods, as it provides reference benchmark data with characteristics resembling natural objects. It can benefit anyone interested in developing new approximate symmetry detection methods and performing comparisons between these methods. The geometric data of trees and manually identified approximate symmetry planes can be directly used as reference data for approximate symmetry detection methods. Additionally, the generated 3D tree models and tree skeleton can be used in other applications requiring pregenerated tree models, such as compression, instancing, decimation for visualization, radiative transfer modeling, and simulation of forest management and horticultural practices. The dataset also provides learning datasets for new machine learning applications, such as approximate symmetry detection and tree detection.
collection_explanation:
The dataset was collected through a multi-step process. First, parameters for each tree species were defined. Then, multiple trees of each species were generated using the particle flow simulation method. The tree models were then exported and processed with an application to manually define the symmetry plane for each tree. 

The dataset contains geometric data of branches, manually defined parameters for tree synthesis, point clouds, and a division plane with a score of bilateral symmetry strength. The trees in the dataset are approximately symmetric, with a manually identified predominant symmetry plane for each tree. 

The data set is organized into 10 folders, each representing a different tree species. Each folder contains data for ten trees, which are numbered consecutively. The dataset also includes an MTL file with material settings for visualizing the tree branches. 

The collected data has several potential uses. It can be used as benchmark data for verifying approximate reflectional symmetry detection methods. The geometric data and manually identified symmetry planes can be used as reference data for approximate symmetry detection methods. The 3D tree models and tree skeleton can be used in various applications, such as compression of tree models, instancing, decimation for visualization, radiative transfer modeling, and simulation of forest management and horticultural practices. Additionally, the dataset can serve as a learning dataset for new machine learning applications related to approximate symmetry detection and tree detection.

The tools, devices, and infrastructure used during the collection process include:

1. Particle flow simulation method: This method was used to generate multiple trees of each species with manually defined parameters.

2. Application for symmetry plane definition: An application was used to manually define the symmetry plane for each tree model.

3. CloudCompare: This application was used to convert the 3D tree models into LAS files.

4. MTL file: This file contains material settings for visualization of tree branches.

Overall, the data collection process involved the use of simulation methods, manual annotation, and specific software applications for processing and visualization.

This was done by visually identifying the main symmetric plane for each tree. The generated tree models were then converted into LAS files using the CloudCompare application. The dataset also includes manually specified parameters for each tree, such as the shape of the tree crown boundary. The annotated approximate symmetry planes and defined tree synthesis parameters can be used as reference data for approximate symmetry detection methods.

uses_data:
The collected data in this study includes X-ray diffraction (XRD) intensity plots, scanning electron microscopy (SEM) micrographs, energy dispersion spectrograph (EDS) maps, and EDS point-and-shoot compositions. The XRD data was obtained using a Bruker D8 Discover X-ray diffractometer, while the SEM/EDS data was acquired using an unspecified instrument. 

The XRD data includes intensity plots for both the as-cast and annealed samples of NbTiVZr. The raw data was background subtracted and the peaks were fitted to Pearson VII shape functions using PeakFit v4. This XRD data provides information on the crystal structure and phase composition of the alloy before and after annealing.

The SEM micrographs provide visual information on the microstructure of the alloy, while the EDS maps and point-and-shoot compositions provide compositional information at specific locations. These SEM/EDS data can be used to analyze the distribution of elements within the alloy and to study any chemical segregation that may occur during annealing.

Overall, this dataset provides valuable information for the scientific community. It demonstrates that a single-phase is not achievable at a cooling rate of approximately 2 C/min for the NbTiVZr high-entropy alloy. This information, combined with similar work on this system, can be used to determine the threshold cooling rate required to achieve a single-phase. Additionally, this dataset is useful for diffusivity research as it shows that the sluggish diffusion often associated with high-entropy alloys does not overpower the thermodynamically-driven chemical segregation of NbTiVZr at low temperatures.
collection_explanation:
The dataset was collected through a series of experimental procedures. First, a NbTiVZr sample was cut into a 1 cm diameter disk and polished. X-ray diffraction (XRD) was performed using a Bruker D8 Discover X-ray diffractometer with copper K-a x-rays. The primary body centred cubic (bcc) peaks were identified and smoothed using Lorentz peak fitting software. Additional peaks suggesting hexagonal closed packed (hcp) alpha and secondary bcc phases were also observed. 

Next, half of the sample was wrapped in Ta foil to prevent leaching and annealed at 1200 C for 24 hours in a Carbolite CTF 12 vacuum tube furnace. The sample was then allowed to cool at a rate of approximately 2 C/min. XRD was performed again to analyze the changes in the microstructure after annealing.

To further analyze the microstructure, a Zeiss LEO scanning electron microscope equipped with energy dispersion spectrograph (EDS) was used. EDS scans were performed to analyze the composition of the annealed specimen. Points 5, 6, and 8 were placed over distinct regions within the microstructure and yielded different concentrations of Ti and Zr. These regions were denoted as a1 and a2.

The dataset includes XRD intensity plots, SEM micrographs, EDS maps, and EDS point-and-shoot compositions. XRD data was background subtracted and fitted to Pearson VII shape functions using PeakFit v4 software.

The value of this dataset lies in its contribution to the understanding of single-phase high-entropy alloys. It shows that achieving a single-phase in the NbTiVZr HEA is not possible at a cooling rate of approximately 2 C/min. This information, combined with similar work on this system, can be used to determine the threshold cooling rate required to achieve a single-phase. Additionally, the dataset provides qualitative insights into diffusivity research by demonstrating that sluggish diffusion does not overpower the thermodynamically-driven chemical segregation of NbTiVZr at low temperatures.

1. Bruker D8 Discover X-ray diffractometer: Used for X-ray diffraction (XRD) analysis of the sample.
2. Lorentz peak fitting software PeakFit v4 and CrystalDiffract: Used for peak fitting and smoothing of the XRD data.
3. Carbolite CTF 12 vacuum tube furnace: Used for annealing the sample at 1200°C for 24 hours.
4. Zeiss LEO scanning electron microscope (SEM) equipped with energy dispersion spectrograph (EDS): Used for analyzing the microstructure of the annealed specimen.
5. Ta foil: Used to wrap half of the sample to prevent leaching during annealing.
6. SEM BSE images: Used to visualize the microstructure of the post-annealed sample.
7. SEM-EDS images: Used to analyze the elemental composition of the post-annealed microstructure.
8. Point scans: Used to measure the atomic % of each element at specific points on the sample.
9. Tables and figures: Used to present and analyze the collected data.

Overall, XRD, SEM, and EDS techniques were used in combination with specific equipment and software to collect and analyze the data.

Figure 2 shows SEM BSE images of the NbTiVZr sample in the post-annealed condition. Figure 3 shows SEM-EDS images of the NbTiVZr post-annealed microstructure. Figure 4 shows the position of point scans corresponding to Table 1. Table 1 provides the average composition of the bulk annealed sample, while Table 2 provides the measured atomic % of each element at points corresponding to Figure 4. The transparency document associated with the article can be found online, and there is also a specifications table that provides details about the annealing process of NbTiVZr at 1200 C with a slow cooling rate.

uses_data:
The collected data consists of two datasets: the "Population dataset" and the "O.O.D. dataset". The "Population dataset" contains synthetic data for 10,000 liver disorder patients, with each row representing one patient. There are a total of 70 columns, each representing a different clinical characteristic or feature of the patients. These features are binary, indicating the presence or absence of a comorbidity or intervention, or ordinal, such as age categories. The "O.O.D. dataset" contains 500 synthetic patients and was generated by changing the prior probabilities of sex, age, and hospitalization. 

The data was generated using a Bayesian network documented in a previous study. The structure of the network, including the nodes, arcs, and prior probabilities, was obtained from the bnlearn package in R. The synthetic data was generated using the rbn() function, with the number of samples set to 10,000 for the "Population dataset". A modified network with different prior probability distributions was used to generate the "O.O.D. dataset". The prior probabilities of sex, age, and hospitalization were changed in this dataset.

The resulting datasets were saved as comma-separated value (csv) files. The "Population dataset" contains data for 10,000 patients, while the "O.O.D. dataset" contains data for 500 patients. These datasets were used to train and test machine learning models, with "hospitalization" as the desired outcome or class to predict. The performance of different classifiers was evaluated on both identically distributed (i.i.d.) datasets and the O.O.D. test set. The study also examined the impact of dataset shift on explanations built by their XAI method, showing that they are more unstable when evaluated on unreliable O.O.D. samples.
collection_explanation:
The dataset was collected using the bnlearn package in R. The Hepar2.rda file from the bnlearn repository was downloaded and loaded into the package. This file contains the Bayesian network structure, including the nodes, arcs, and prior probabilities. 

To generate the synthetic data, the rbn() function was used. This function takes as input the loaded network structure and the number of samples to generate. In this case, 10,000 samples were generated to create an initial set of patients called the "population dataset". The code used to generate this dataset can be found at the provided GitHub link.

A second set of synthetic patients called the "out-of-distribution (O.O.D) dataset" was generated by modifying the prior probabilities of sex, age, and hospitalization. The prior probability distribution of sex was changed from p(female) = 0.6 to p(female) = 0.4 (and subsequently, p(male) = 0.6). The "hospitalization" distribution was changed from p(hospitalization = absent) = 0.65 to 0.35. The age probability distribution was set as p(age between 0 and 30) = 0.1, p(age between 31 and 50) = 0.3, p(age between 51 and 65) = 0.5, and p(age higher than 65) = 0.1. The resulting data from these modifications were saved into CSV files.

Users can customize the collection process by changing parameters such as the number of patients or prior probabilities to simulate their own cohort of liver disorder patients.

The obtained datasets were used to train and test machine learning models, with "hospitalization" selected as the desired outcome to predict. The 10,000 patients from the "population dataset" were used as the "true population", and a subset of these patients was sampled for training and parameter tuning. The remaining patients were kept as an "inner distributed" test set. The O.O.D dataset of 500 patients was used as an additional O.O.D test set.

In summary, the dataset was collected by simulating patients using a Bayesian network and modifying the prior probabilities to generate different datasets.

2. Bayesian network: The data was generated by sampling from a Bayesian network describing liver disorder patients.

3. Hepar2.rda file: The Hepar2.rda file from the bnlearn repository was downloaded and used as the initial network structure.

4. Synthetic data generation script: A script was used to generate synthetic data based on the loaded network structure and the number of samples to generate.

5. GitHub repository: The code for generating the synthetic data and modifying the prior probabilities was stored in a GitHub repository.

6. CSV files: The resulting synthetic data was saved into CSV files for further analysis and use in machine learning models.

7. Colab file: An interactive visualization of the Bayesian network used for generating the data was provided in a Colab file.

Overall, the collection process involved using R and the bnlearn package to generate synthetic data based on a Bayesian network, modifying the prior probabilities, and saving the data into CSV files.
annotation_explanation: The annotation process done over the data involves the creation of synthetic patient profiles using a Bayesian network. The data is generated for liver disorder patients and includes different clinical characteristics or features. The data is provided in two files: HEPAR_simulated_patients.csv, which contains synthetic data for 10,000 liver disorder patients (population dataset), and HEPAR_simulated_patients_ood.csv, which contains 500 synthetic patients with modified prior probabilities of sex, age, and hospitalization (O.O.D. dataset). The features in the data are binary, indicating the presence or absence of comorbidities or interventions, and ordinal, such as age categories. The synthetic data can be used to train and test machine learning models, particularly for investigating model behavior, inspection, debugging, and testing robustness, reliability, and explainability.

uses_data:
The collected data in this study includes small-angle X-ray scattering (SAXS) measurements and a concatenated file containing 70 refined structures. 

The SAXS measurements were performed using a SAXSess mc 2 instrument equipped with a sealed-tube source and a CMOS diode array detector. The proteins were dialyzed to remove any high molecular-weight aggregates. The SAXS data were collected every 30 minutes to ensure the stability of the protein sample. The frames were compared, and if there were no differences among them, they were combined. The SAXS data could not be fitted to any single known structure, as the protein adopts multiple conformations in solution. The SAXS data represent the direct averaging of the scattering profiles for the different conformational states in solution.

The concatenated file contains 70 refined structures and was deposited at the Protein Data Bank (PDB). These structures were calculated with various starting coordinates and are slightly different due to a structural convergence problem. Each structure in the file represents four conformers, which correspond to alternative locations of the protein units. Since the protein cannot be in all four locations simultaneously, the atomic entries in the PDB file were given an occupancy of 0.25.
collection_explanation:
The dataset was collected using small-angle X-ray scattering (SAXS) measurements on a SAXSess mc 2 instrument. The proteins were dialyzed to remove any high molecular-weight aggregates. The Ub 2 protein was centrifuged to further remove aggregates, and the upper portion of the supernatant was collected for SAXS measurement. To ensure the stability of the protein sample, SAXS data were collected every 30 minutes and compared. If there were no differences among the frames, they were combined. 

The SAXS data were used to study the conformational states of Ub 2 in solution. As Ub 2 adopts multiple conformations, the SAXS data could not be fitted to any single known structure. The SAXS technique is insensitive to transient noncovalent interactions between Ub 2 proteins, and the data represent the direct averaging of the scattering profiles for the conformational states in solution.

In addition to SAXS, paramagnetic NMR, specifically paramagnetic relaxation enhancement (PRE), was used to provide long-range distance information and depict protein conformational fluctuations. Paramagnetic NMR was performed with the conjugation of an extrinsic paramagnetic probe. The PRE value is related to the inverse sixth power of the distance between the paramagnetic center and a protein nucleus. The exact position of the paramagnetic center is not fixed, which can cause variations in the PRE value. The observed PRE value for a protein nucleus in a certain conformational state is a product of the PRE values and the relative populations.

The dataset also includes integrated data from isothermal calorimetry (ITC) and small-angle X-ray scattering (SAXS). SAXS data define the overall silhouette of the protein system but lack structural details, while ITC measures the binding affinities between Ub 2 and its protein ligands. By assessing the changes in binding affinities, the relative populations of the preexisting Ub 2 conformational states can be extrapolated.

The Ub 2 ensemble structure consists of 70 refined structures deposited in the Protein Data Bank (PDB). Each structure represents alternative locations of the proximal Ub unit, with the distal Ub unit fixed. As the Ub 2 cannot be in all four locations simultaneously, the atomic entries in the PDB file were given an occupancy of 0.25.

collection_infrastructure:
The tools, devices, and infrastructure used during the collection process include:
- SAXSess mc 2 instrument (Anton Paar, Graz, Austria) equipped with a sealed-tube source and a CMOS diode array detector
- Centrifuge (used to remove high molecular-weight aggregates)
- Dialysis equipment (used to extensively dialyze the proteins)
- PDB (Protein Data Bank) for depositing the refined structures
- NMR (Nuclear Magnetic Resonance) for quantitative assessment of protein ensemble structure
- ITC (Isothermal Titration Calorimetry) for quantitative assessment of protein ensemble structure
annotation_explanation: The annotation process done over the data involves characterizing the structures of the two alternative closed states of Ub 2 using paramagnetic NMR and integrating data from small angle X-ray scattering (SAXS) and isothermal calorimetry (ITC) to assess the relative occupancies for each conformational state. The data from paramagnetic NMR provides long-range distance information and allows the depiction of protein conformational fluctuations. The PRE value, which is related to the inverse sixth power of the distance between the paramagnetic center and a protein nucleus, is used to determine the occupancy of each conformational state. The data from SAXS defines the overall silhouette of the protein system, while ITC measures the binding affinities between Ub 2 and its protein ligands. Changes in binding affinities allow the extrapolation of the relative populations of the preexisting Ub 2 conformational states. The ensemble structure of Ub 2 consists of 70 refined structures, each comprising four conformers representing alternative locations of the proximal Ub unit. The atomic entries in the PDB file were given an occupancy of 0.25 to account for the fact that Ub 2 cannot be in all four locations at the same time.

uses_data:
The collected data in this study includes survey responses on patterns of utilization of mental healthcare services among people living with mental illness. The data is significant because it can be used to monitor the availability and utilization of mental health services. It can also be replicated in other countries with similar demographic factors and used in the overall study of mental health.

The data is presented in several figures and tables. Figure 1 shows the perceived use of mental healthcare services by the respondents. Figure 2 shows the perceived frequency of use of these services. Figure 3 displays the frequency of taking prescribed medications. Figure 4 presents the perceived obstacles of using available mental healthcare services. Figure 5 is a biplot that shows the perceived relationship in graphical form.

Tables 1 and 2 contain contingency analysis between the usage or hindrance of mental services and socio-demographic variables. Tables 3 and 4 show correlational analysis between the usage or hindrance of mental services and socio-demographic variables. Table 5 is a correspondence table of patterns of utilization of mental healthcare services. Table 6 provides a model summary of these patterns. Table 7 and Table 8 are overview row points and overview column points tables, respectively, of patterns of utilization of mental healthcare services.

Correspondence analysis was performed to visually display the contributions of the income of the respondents to the hindrance from using mental health services. The results of this analysis are presented in Table 5, Table 6, Table 7, Table 8, and Figure 5. The p value indicates that the income of the respondents is not associated with the hindrance they encountered in the utilization of mental healthcare services.
collection_explanation:
The dataset was collected through a field survey using structured questionnaires. The survey was administered to People Living with Mental Illness (PLWMI) and their caregivers. The aim of the survey was to measure the patterns of utilization of mental healthcare services among PLWMI. Only those receiving treatments and their caregivers were considered for the study. Additionally, only residents of Yoruba origin in the study areas were included, while adults younger than 18 years were excluded.

The patterns of utilization of mental healthcare services were determined based on several factors, including the perceived use of the services by the respondents, the frequency of use, the frequency of taking prescribed medications, and the perceived obstacles in using the available mental healthcare services. These patterns are presented in Figures 1, 2, 3, and 4 of the document.

The dataset includes various tables and figures that provide analysis and summary of the collected data. Table 1 presents a contingency analysis between the usage of mental services and socio-demographic variables. Table 2 presents a contingency analysis between the perceived hindrance of mental services and socio-demographic variables. Table 3 presents a correlational analysis between the usage of mental services and socio-demographic variables. Table 4 presents a correlational analysis between the perceived hindrance of mental services and socio-demographic variables.

Table 5 is a correspondence table that shows the patterns of utilization of mental healthcare services among people living with mental illness. Table 6 is a model summary of these patterns. Table 7 presents the overview row points, and Table 8 presents the overview column points of the patterns of utilization of mental healthcare services.

In addition to the tables, there are also figures that visually represent the data. Figure 5 is a biplot that shows the perceived relationship in graphical form.

The raw data of the survey can be accessed as Supplementary data 1, and the questionnaire used in the survey can be accessed as Supplementary data 2.

collection_sources: The data has been collected from People Living with Mental Illness (PLWMI) and their caregivers through structured questionnaires.
collection_infrastructure: The tools, devices, and infrastructure used during the collection process include structured questionnaires, correspondence analysis, tables (1-8), and figures (1-5).
annotation_explanation: The annotation process done over the data includes the use of various visual displays and statistical analyses. Correspondence analysis is performed to visually display the contributions of the income of the respondents to the hindrance from using mental health services. This analysis is further supported by contingency analysis and correlational analysis between the usage of mental services and the socio-demographic variables. The results of these analyses are presented in tables and figures, such as the correspondence table, model summary, overview row points, overview column points, and biplot. These visual displays and statistical analyses provide insights into the perceived use of mental healthcare services, frequency of use, obstacles faced, and the relationship between socio-demographic variables and the utilization of mental healthcare services.

uses_uses:
The recommended uses of the dataset are: 
1. Integration with the human proteome project data.
2. Use by urologists for a better understanding of urogenital tract pathophysiology.
3. Identification of ureter disease-associated biomarkers, such as ureter carcinoma.
4. Examination of Cytoscape GO annotation to better understand proteins' molecular function, biological processes, and cellular component.
5. Use as a valuable resource for researchers working in the field of urology and urine biomarker discovery.
