uses_data_limits: No, there is no mention about non-recommended uses or generalization limits of the data.
uses_represents_people: No. The data of the dataset represents wrecks, not people.
uses_collected_from_people: No. The subjects of the collection process are wrecks and artificial reefs, not humans.
uses_data:
The collected data in this study consists of records of wrecks that have been used as artificial reefs. The data includes information such as the citation, latitude and longitude coordinates, type of structure, and lifespan of the wreck as an artificial reef. The lifespan of the wrecks was calculated based on the type of structure and material, using estimates provided by 36 studies that monitor the colonization of artificial reefs. For these 36 wrecks, additional information is included, such as the purpose of deployment, method of sinking, baseline study before monitoring, purpose of monitoring, method of monitoring, and a brief summary of monitoring outcomes.

Biophysical marine factors in each wreck location were extracted from Feldman & McClain and the World Ocean Database. This information includes data on pH, chlorophyll A concentration, calcite, and sea surface temperature. The Euclidean distance between coral reefs and deployed wrecks was calculated using data on corals' location from the Coral Traits Database. The study also indicates whether the wreck is located within a protected area, using information from the World Database on Protected Areas.

Data regarding wrecks as artificial reefs in the rest of the world was obtained from diving websites and scientific publications. Information about 1901 sites of intentionally deployed wrecks globally was gathered, including the name of the wreck or reef site, year of deployment, type of wreck, location, coordinates, depth, accuracy of the coordinates, last update of the information, source of the information, and any additional notes. The coordinates were given in decimal degrees to allow for direct use with other spatial information. The data contains records of 130 types of wrecks, which were aggregated into 12 categories.
collection_explanation:
The dataset was collected through a combination of sources, including diving websites, scientific publications, and government reports. The researchers gathered information about 1901 sites of wrecks that were intentionally deployed as artificial reefs globally. The main fields included in the database were the name of the wreck or reef site, year of deployment, type of wreck, location, coordinates, depth, accuracy of the coordinates, last update of the information, source of the information, and notes.

To ensure quality control, the data entries were checked by at least one person who was not responsible for data input. Two people had access to the dataset at the same time, with one person attributing a random record number to the other person. The second person was then responsible for finding the relevant data from the source documents, such as coordinates, name, year of deployment, and depth. The two individuals cross-referenced the data with the source to check for errors.

The dataset contains records of 130 types of wrecks, which were aggregated into 12 categories. Each wreck record includes the citation, latitude and longitude coordinates, type of structure, and the lifespan of the wreck as an artificial reef. The lifespan of the wrecks was calculated based on the type of structure and material, using estimates provided by 36 studies that monitor the colonization of artificial reefs.

In addition to the main dataset, there are also tables and figures in the document that provide additional information and visualizations of the data. These include figures showing the global distribution of wrecks, the number of intentionally deployed wrecks by location and year, and a comparison of the number of wrecks globally excluding the USA. There are also tables that provide an overview of the distribution of wrecks in the USA and the rest of the world, the number of deployed wrecks by country, and a description of the variables in the main dataset.

- Coral Traits Database
- World Database on Protected Areas [2]
collection_infrastructure:
The tools, devices, and infrastructure used during the collection process include:

- ArcGIS software (version 10.5.1) was used to generate maps and calculate the Euclidean distance between coral reefs and deployed wrecks.
- Diving websites and scientific publications were used as sources of data regarding wrecks as artificial reefs.
- The World Ocean Database and Feldman & McClain were used to extract biophysical marine factors in each wreck location.
- The Coral Traits Database was used to obtain species-specific biogeographic locations of corals.
- The World Database on Protected Areas was used to determine if the wreck is located within a protected area.

One person assigned a random record number to the other person, who then had to find the relevant data from the source documents. The two people cross-referenced the data with the source to check for errors. Additionally, biophysical marine factors were extracted from other sources and included in the dataset. The data was then visualized using ArcGIS software.

authoring_funding: Yes, this work has been funded by the National Natural Science Foundation of China grants 31370042 and 31000966.
authoring_funding_grant_id: The mentioned grant reference numbers in the context are 31370042 and 31000966.
authoring_maintenance_policies: No, there is no mention about maintenance policies of the dataset in the context.
uses_uses:
The recommended uses of the dataset are: 
1. To study gene rearrangements and gene duplications in mitochondrial genomes of praying mantises.
2. To serve as a model for future research on gene rearrangements and gene duplications in other insect mitochondrial genomes.
3. To aid in the analysis of phylogenetic relationships within Mantodea.
4. To provide a primer strategy that can be widely used for amplifying insect mitochondrial genomes and reduce experimental workload.
5. To calculate nucleotide diversity of protein-coding genes among 27 mantises.
uses_ml_approach: Yes, the dataset has been tested using machine learning approaches. ML (Maximum Likelihood) and BI (Bayesian Inference) analyses were implemented using different data sets (PCG123, PCG123R, PCG12, PCG12R, and PCGAA) to infer the phylogenetic relationships within Mantodea. The results from these analyses are presented in figures and discussed in the main text.
uses_data_limits: No, there is no mention about non-recommended uses or generalization limits of the data.
uses_represents_people: No. The data of the dataset does not represent people. The dataset is about the mitochondrial genomes of praying mantises and their phylogenetic relationships.
uses_collected_from_people: No. The subjects of the collection process are not humans. The dataset consists of mitochondrial genomes of praying mantises.
uses_data:
The collected data in this study consists of mitochondrial genomes of praying mantises and the phylogenetic relationships within the Mantodea order. The dataset used for the phylogenetic analysis includes protein-coding genes (PCG) and tRNA genes. 

Figure 1 shows the phylogenetic relationships analyzed using ML methods with the dataset 13PCG. The black box at each node indicates a bootstrap value (BP) of 75 or higher. Small boxes represent tRNA genes, and an asterisk-labeled box represents a pseudogene.

Figure 3 shows the phylogenetic relationships analyzed using ML methods with the dataset 13PCG12R. The black box at each node indicates a bootstrap value (BP) of 0.75 or higher. Small boxes represent tRNA genes, and an asterisk-labeled box represents a pseudogene.

Figure 5 shows the phylogenetic relationships analyzed using BI methods with the dataset 13PCG12R. The black box at each node indicates a posterior probability (PP) of 0.95 or higher. Small boxes represent tRNA genes, and an asterisk-labeled box represents a pseudogene.

Figure 8 illustrates the primer strategy used in the study. Double-headed arrows indicate the location of the DNA fragment amplified by PCR with each pair of primers. The primer DNA sequences associated with each fragment can be found in Table 1.

Figure 7 presents the nucleotide diversity of protein-coding genes among 27 mantises.

Table 1 provides information on the initiation codon (I codon), termination codon (T codon), and amino acid length of protein-coding genes among the 27 mantises.

The transparency document and supporting information can be found in the online version of the article.
collection_explanation: The dataset was collected through a routine experimental approach. The researchers extracted total DNA from 27 mantises and used PCR and sequencing to acquire the whole mitochondrial genomes. They then performed sequence analyses, including assembly, annotation, and alignment. Phylogenetic relationships were constructed using five different data sets, which included the mitochondrial genomes of 46 samples, including 15 previously sequenced mantis mitogenomes, as well as the mitogenomes of two cockroaches and two termites as outgroups. The researchers used ML and BI analyses to analyze the data sets. PartitionFinder was used to determine the optimal partitioning strategy and choose the best model. The nucleotide diversity of protein-coding genes among the 27 mantises was calculated using DnaSP v5. The primer strategy used for amplifying the mantis mitochondrial genomes is shown in Figure 8, and the primer sequences are provided in the main text. The initiation codon, termination codon, amino acid length, and nucleotide diversity of protein-coding genes among the 27 mantises are also provided in Table 1. The dataset includes five different datasets of mantis mitochondrial genomes, which were used to construct phylogenetic relationships within Mantodea. The phylogenetic trees were inferred from Bayesian analysis using two data sets (PCG12R, PCGAA) and Maximum Likelihood analysis using four data sets (PCG123, PCG12, PCG12R, and PCGAA). The whole mitochondrial genomes of the 27 mantises have been submitted to GenBank with the accession numbers KY689112-KY689138.
collection_team_type: The data was collected by an internal team.
collection_team_demographic: No, there is no mention of demographic information about the team who collects the data.
collection_sources:
The data has been collected from the following sources or subjects:
- Mantodea (praying mantises)
- Mitochondrial genomes of 27 mantises
- Two cockroaches
- Two termites
collection_infrastructure: The tools, devices, and infrastructure used during the collection process include total DNA extraction, PCR (Polymerase Chain Reaction), sequencing, assembly, annotation, alignment, RAxML 8.2.0 (for ML analysis), MrBayes 3.2 (for BI analysis), and PartitionFinder 1.1.1 (for inferring the optimal partitioning strategy and choosing the best model). DnaSP v5 was used to calculate the nucleotide diversity of protein-coding genes. The primer strategy shown in Figure 8 was used for amplifying the mantis mitochondrial genomes.
annotation_explanation: The annotation process done over the data involves analyzing the phylogenetic relationships of Mantodea using different methods such as Maximum Likelihood (ML) and Bayesian Inference (BI). Five different data sets were used for the analysis, including PCG123, PCG123R, PCG12, PCG12R, and PCGAA. The phylogenetic trees were constructed based on these data sets, and nodal supports were provided to indicate the confidence in the relationships. Additionally, the initiation codon, termination codon, amino acid length of protein-coding genes, and nucleotide diversity of protein-coding genes among 27 mantises were also analyzed and compared. The results of the annotation process are presented in figures and tables in the main text of the document.

uses_uses:
The recommended uses of the dataset are: 
1. To illustrate the manufacturing process of a novel glass-glass composite scaffold with biomedical potential.
2. To show the hierarchical porous structure of the scaffolds, which is needed in biomaterials intended for bone repair.
3. To show the release kinetics of cell-influencing ions (Calcium, Phosphorous, Silicon, Potassium, and Boron) upon immersion in simulated body fluid (SBF).
4. To demonstrate how the release kinetics is influenced by nitridation, which can be used by other material scientists interested in modifying the degradability and ion-release of their bioglasses.

uses_represents_people: No. The data of the dataset does not represent people. The dataset is describing the preparation and characterization of a bioactive glass scaffold.
uses_collected_from_people: No. The subjects of the collection process are not humans. The data collected in this study pertains to the manufacturing process of a glass-glass composite scaffold and the release kinetics of various ions when the scaffolds are immersed in a simulated body fluid.
uses_data:
The collected data in this study includes information on the manufacturing process of a glass-glass composite scaffold with biomedical potential. The data demonstrates the hierarchical porous structure of the scaffolds, which is important for biomaterials intended for bone repair. Additionally, the data shows the release kinetics of various cell-influencing ions (Calcium, Phosphorous, Silicon, Potassium, and Boron) when the scaffolds are immersed in a simulated body fluid (SBF). The data also examines how the release kinetics are influenced by nitridation, which could be useful for other material scientists interested in modifying the degradability and ion-release of their bioglasses.

The experimental design involved synthesizing porous glass scaffolds (ICIE16/BSG and ICIE16/BSG-NITRI) as described in a previous publication. The scaffolds were then immersed in SBF solution at 37 °C for up to 168 hours (7 days). The release of Calcium, Phosphorous, Silicon, Potassium, and Boron ions into the SBF solution was measured daily using Plasma emission spectroscopy. Weight changes of the scaffolds were also calculated and plotted against time.

The data is available with the article and can be accessed by other researchers interested in the manufacturing process of glass-glass composites or studying the release kinetics of cell-influencing ions. The study was co-supported by various funding sources and acknowledgments are given to individuals who contributed to the research.
collection_explanation:
The dataset was collected through a series of steps. First, the porous glass scaffolds ICIE16/BSG and ICIE16/BSG-NITRI were synthesized using a combination of gel casting and foam replication techniques. These scaffolds were then nitrided with a hot ammonia flow to create the ICIE16/BSG-NITRI bioglass.

To evaluate the bioactivity of the bioglasses, they were immersed in simulated body fluid (SBF) for a period of seven days. The SBF solution was prepared according to the method described by Kokubo et al. The ratio of 1 gram of scaffold to 100 ml of SBF was used in all experiments.

During the immersion period, the concentration of calcium, phosphorous, silicon, potassium, and boron ions released into the SBF solution was measured daily using plasma emission spectroscopy (ICP-OES). Weight changes of the scaffolds were also calculated using the formula ΔWt = 100 * (W0 - Wt) / W0, where W0 is the initial mass and Wt is the mass at time t.

The changes in ion concentration and weight of the scaffolds were plotted against time. Fig. 3 shows the changes in calcium, phosphorous, silicon, and potassium concentration in the SBF solution over time. It can be observed that the concentration of phosphorous decreases while the concentration of calcium, silicon, and potassium increases.

Fig. 4 illustrates the changes in boron content in the SBF solution after immersion of the non-nitrided ICIE16/BSG and nitrided ICIE16/BSG-NITRI bioglasses. At shorter immersion times, the amount of boron released was lower for the nitrided glasses, but this trend was inverted at longer times.

In summary, the dataset was collected by synthesizing the bioglasses, immersing them in SBF solution, and measuring the concentration of released ions and weight changes over time.

annotation_explanation: The annotation process done over the data involves summarizing the sequential steps of the processing method of ICIE16/BSG bioglasses, observing the resulting porous 3D scaffolds, and collecting data on the changes in calcium, phosphorous, silicon, potassium, and boron concentrations in the SBF over time. The annotation also includes noting the influence of nitridation on the release kinetics of these ions and how it can be used by other material scientists interested in modifying the degradability and ion-release of their bioglasses.

uses_data: The collected data in this study includes information on the connectivity of transport in a specific region, as well as the main types of agricultural production in that region. The data can be used by regional authorities to identify priority areas for the development of the agroindustrial complex, and by investors planning to develop agriculture in the Far Eastern Federal District. The data can also be used by other researchers to determine the export orientation of agricultural and processing enterprises, and to identify potential foreign markets for manufactured products. The data includes information on processed fish and canned fish, crustaceans and mollusks, as well as vegetable oils and their fractions. The data is available in the Harvard Dataverse repository and is sourced from the Federal State Statistics Service.
collection_explanation:
The dataset was collected using a combination of state and information systems of the Russian Federation and open information systems of commercial digital aggregators. The researchers connected to the ArcGIS 10.6 software package to access the following information systems for vector representation of the territorial characteristics of the Asian part of the Russian Federation: the state information system "Public Cadastral Map," remote sensing data from the specialized mapping service Living Atlas ESRI, the ESRI1 open geoinformation project for the Asian continent, the Limited Liability Company "Exmile Solutions Project for Open Maritime Traffic Tracking," and Earth remote sensing materials from a specialized Google mapping service.

The collected data is valuable as it has practical focus and applicability. The methodology and software tools used can be applied to assess the connectivity of transport in any region. When combined with the identification of the main types of agricultural production in the region, the data can be used to identify main investment areas and promising projects. Regional authorities can use this data to identify priority areas for the development of the agroindustrial complex of the region. Investors planning to develop agriculture in the Far Eastern Federal District will also find the data presented to be of interest. The research expands the areas of investment in not only the agri-food sector but also in transportation and infrastructure facilities that affect the sustainable development of rural areas. Other researchers can use the data to determine the export orientation of agricultural and region processing enterprises and identify potential promising foreign markets for manufactured products. The research also identifies the topical directions of the development of agricultural and processing enterprises in the Far Eastern Federal District.

uses_uses:
The recommended uses of the dataset are: 
1. Analysis of energy consumption and expenditure of manufacturing and agroindustrial firms in the Philippines.
2. Crafting policies and guidelines on energy-related concerns such as energy efficiency and transition to clean energy.
3. Analysis of the likelihood of switching from conventional to alternative fuels in major manufacturing and industrial production processes.
4. Development of longitudinal studies to capture how technological changes influence the demand and usage of various fuels.
5. Scaling the size of data collection to include other manufacturing and industrial firms outside the special economic zones.
6. Evaluating how knowledge and perceptions toward alternative fuel can shape future demand.
uses_ml_approach: No, there is no mention about any test using a machine learning approach.
uses_data_limits: No, there is no mention about non-recommended uses or generalization limits of the data.
uses_represents_people: No. The data of the dataset does not represent people. The dataset includes non-personal and non-identifiable information gathered from the survey. Information such as firm and respondent names and contact information were permanently deleted in compliance with data privacy protection laws and research ethics protocols.
uses_collected_from_people: No. The subjects of the collection process are firms operating inside manufacturing and agro-industrial special economic zones in the Philippines, not humans.
uses_data: The collected data consists of information gathered from firms operating inside manufacturing and agro-industrial special economic zones in the Philippines. The data includes details about the firm's profile, production schedule and operation, utilities, energy efficiency initiatives, fuels used in production, aptitude on alternative fuels and primary energies, and business considerations. The data set is organized in a .csv format, with each row representing the responses of a unique firm. A unique firm identification number was generated to aid data users, with the first two digits representing the province, the next two digits representing the city or municipality, followed by two digits for the economic zone, and the last three digits representing the firm. The data set only includes non-personal and non-identifiable information, as firm and respondent names and contact information were permanently deleted to comply with data privacy protection laws and research ethics protocols. Each column in the data set is headed by a variable name, which starts with the section number and question number, followed by keywords for the summary of the question, unit of measure, and response option. For questions that asked for multiple responses, one variable is generated for each response option. The data dictionary, provided in .txt format as Supplementary Appendix 2, describes basic information about each variable, including data type, variable name, and variable label. Numeric data are represented as byte, int, long, float, or double, while string data are represented as "str" followed by the maximum number of characters. The data set is valuable for analyzing the energy consumption and expenditure behavior of large and intensive users, such as manufacturing and agro-industrial firms in the Philippines, as well as evaluating how knowledge and perceptions toward alternative fuel can shape future demand.
collection_explanation:
The dataset was collected through an online survey using the subscription-based platform SurveyMonkey. The raw data is available in .csv format in Supplementary Appendix 1. Each row in the dataset represents the responses of a unique firm. A unique firm identification number was generated to aid data users, with the firm ID ("locatorid" variable) containing nine digits. The first two digits represent the province, the next two digits represent the city or municipality, followed by two digits for the economic zone, and the last three digits represent the firm.

To ensure data privacy and comply with research ethics protocols, personal and identifiable information such as firm and respondent names and contact information were permanently deleted from the database. The dataset only includes non-personal and non-identifiable information gathered from the survey.

The structure of the dataset follows the same organization as the survey questionnaire. Each column in the dataset is headed by a variable name, which starts with the section number and question number, followed by keywords for the summary of the question, unit of measure, and response option. For example, the variable "sIq1_ecozone" corresponds to Section I Question 1 on ecozone. The data dictionary in Supplementary Appendix 2 provides basic information about each variable, including data type, variable name, and variable label.

For questions that asked for multiple responses, one variable is generated for each response option. For example, Section III Question 33 asked about the types of fuel used for self-generation of power, and the variables associated with this question are "sIIIq33_selfgen_biodie", "sI-IIq33_selfgen_bunker", etc. For questions that required only one response, the actual response is recorded as it is.

The proposal to conduct the survey and the data collection process were examined and validated exempt from review by the Ateneo de Manila University Research Ethics Committee. Implicit informed consent was obtained from the participants, and they were informed that personal information would be treated with utmost confidentiality. No identifiable information appears in the collected data.

The online survey was conducted using a subscription-based platform called SurveyMonkey. The data was collected in raw format and is available in a .csv file.

Each column in the dataset is headed by a variable name, which starts with the section number and question number followed by keywords for the summary of the question, unit of measure, and response option. The data dictionary (Supplementary Appendix 2) provides basic information about each variable, including its data type, variable name, and variable label. The data type indicates whether the variable assumes numeric or string data. Numeric data are represented as byte, int, long, float, or double, while string data are represented as "str" followed by the maximum number of characters. uses_uses:
The recommended uses of the dataset are: 
1. Development of adsorption systems for the removal of heavy metals from soil, water, and wastewater.
2. Use by engineers involved in biological purification of water, wastewater, and soil refinement.
uses_ml_approach: No, there is no mention about any test using a machine learning approach.
uses_data_limits: No, there is no mention about non-recommended uses or generalization limits of the data.
uses_represents_people: No. The context does not mention anything about the data representing people.
uses_collected_from_people: No. The subjects of the collection process are not humans. The data collected in this study pertains to the concentrations of heavy metals in soil and aqueous solutions, as well as the presence of Pseudomonas aeruginosa.
uses_data:
The collected data in this study is available within the paper and is presented in both raw and analyzed formats. The data is valuable as it suggests a biological adsorption method for the removal of heavy metals from soil and aqueous solutions. This data can be used to develop adsorption systems for the removal of heavy metals from soil, water, and wastewater. It will be particularly useful for engineers involved in the biological purification of water, wastewater, and soil refinement.

The data was acquired through various methods. The concentrations of Cd and Pb were measured using Atomic adsorption (Varian AA 220). The pH levels were measured using a digital pH meter (Metrohm). For final confirmation of the presence of Pseudomonas aeruginosa, PCR was conducted after biochemical tests. The temperature was measured using a digital thermometer (Testo).

Overall, the collected data provides valuable insights into the effectiveness of a biological adsorption method for heavy metal removal and can be used for further research and development in this field.
collection_explanation:
The dataset was collected using various measurement techniques and instruments. The concentrations of Cd and Pb were measured using Atomic adsorption with a Varian AA 220 instrument. The pH levels were measured using a digital pH meter from Metrohm. For final confirmation of the presence of Pseudomonas aeruginosa, PCR was conducted after biochemical tests. The temperature was measured using a digital thermometer from Testo.

The data in the dataset are available within the paper itself. All the biological and chemical materials used in the experiments were provided with a specified degree of purity and were purchased from Merck Company in Germany.

collection_sources: The data has been collected from sources such as Atomic adsorption (Varian AA 220), digital pH meter (Metrohm), PCR for final confirmation of Pseudomonas aeruginosa, and digital thermometer (Testo).
collection_infrastructure:
The tools, devices, and infrastructure used during the collection process include:

- Atomic adsorption (Varian AA 220) for measuring Cd and Pb
- Digital pH meter (Metrohm) for measuring pH
- PCR for final confirmation of Pseudomonas aeruginosa after biochemical tests
- Digital thermometer (Testo) for measuring temperature

uses_uses:
The recommended uses of the dataset are: 
1. Reconstructing environmental conditions in the Holocene valley depositions.
2. Studying Holocene sedimentology in the circum-Alpine region and Late Neolithic Archaeology.
3. Statistical verification of direct push methods for electrical conductivity sensing and Soil Colour Optical Screening Tool.
4. Analyzing and comparing the data with other archaeological sites.
5. Improving the methods of direct-push sensing and comparing it with sedimentological features.
6. Further research on issues in Pestenacker and central Europe, particularly in the circum-Alpine region.
uses_ml_approach: No, there is no mention about any test using a machine learning approach.
uses_data_limits: No, there is no mention about non-recommended uses or generalization limits of the data.
uses_represents_people: No. The data of the dataset does not represent people. The dataset is focused on environmental conditions, sedimentology, and archaeological findings.
uses_collected_from_people: No. The subjects of the collection process are not humans. The data collected includes information about sedimentological findings, stratigraphical units, and features such as charcoal, wood remains, and brick fragments.
uses_data: The collected data consists of raw data and graphical figures of direct push-based electrical conductivity and color logs, as well as driving core recoveries and hand drilling recoveries. The data includes information such as sample labels, exact locations (latitude, longitude, altitude), depth of measurements, and related measurements of electrical conductivity and color. The data sets are organized into transects A to D, with varying numbers of logs and distances between them. The sedimentological findings are classified into eight stratigraphical units, including stratigraphical gaps, precipitated carbonate deposits, organic-rich layers, archaeological layers, freshwater carbonates, peat, and gravel. The data also includes information on certain features such as charcoal, wood remains, and brick fragments. Additionally, the data includes incision levels of former stream courses of the Loosbach, which were determined from unpublished archaeological excavation profiles. The data sets and figures can be used for further analysis, statistical verification of direct push methods, and comparison with other archaeological sites.
collection_explanation:
The dataset was collected using various methods in the study area of the Late Neolithic wetland site of Pestenacker, located in the Loosbach valley. For the Holocene depositions of the Loosbach valley, 297 direct push colour logs and 116 direct push electrical conductivity logs were conducted. The direct push sensing of electrical conductivity was performed using a self-propelled carrier vehicle (Geoprobe) with an attached Geoprobe SC 500 probe. The Soil Optical Color Screening Tool (SCOST TM) was used for sensing visible colors. This tool induces white light and records the reflected light from the sediment in the wavelength range of 350-1000 nm. Raster images, the corresponding color in the Munsell color system, and depth information were computed using the OST-Software. The logs were terminated when the resistance increased. The direct push soundings were leveled using a Topcon HiPer II DGPS system. The detailed raw data of the direct push logs are accessible in the data repository. 

In addition to the direct push logs, 14 driving cores and 20 hand drillings were carried out to generate data on the Holocene depositions. A hand-held Cobra Pro driving core drilling system and a 60 mm diameter open corer were used for the driving cores, while the Edelman-Bohrer with a diameter of 70 mm was used for hand drilling. The recovered parameters included color according to the Munsell Soil Color Chart, estimated carbonate content, grain size of the fine soil, redox features, carbonate concretions, and other layer details. The sedimentological findings were classified into eight stratigraphical units. The detailed raw data of the lithological descriptions are accessible in the data repository.

The incision levels of former stream courses of the Loosbach were generated using unpublished excavation reports. Radiocarbon, archaeological, and historic age controls were assigned to the different stream courses, enabling the development of the stream courses in six different time intervals. The respective age data can be found in the published study.

This includes annotating the RGB raster data of the direct push color logs, the electrical conductivity logs, and the lithological descriptions of the driving cores and hand drillings. The annotations include information such as log numbers, depth of measurements, location coordinates, and color or conductivity values. The annotations also involve identifying and classifying different stratigraphical units and archaeological layers. The annotated data can be used for reconstructing environmental conditions, statistical verification of direct push methods, and comparison with other archaeological sites.

uses_data_limits: No, there is no mention about non-recommended uses or generalization limits of the data.
uses_represents_people: No. The data of the dataset does not represent people. The data represents processed TEOAE data, including amplitudes of TEOAEs in different conditions and the magnitude of suppression of TEOAE for various contralateral noise conditions.
uses_collected_from_people: No. The subjects of the collection process are not humans. The dataset consists of processed Transient Evoked Otoacoustic Emission (TEOAE) data, which is related to hearing sciences and speech perception.
uses_data:
The collected data in this study consists of processed Transient Evoked Otoacoustic Emission (TEOAE) data. The data is provided in a spreadsheet format (.xlsx) and includes information on the global amplitude of TEOAEs, noise floor, and signal-to-noise ratio (SNR) across different conditions. The data was recorded using the ILO v6 analysis software.

The first column in the spreadsheet represents participant ID, and each participant's data is provided in one row. The columns labeled 'BL' represent the amplitude of TEOAE in the baseline condition. The columns labeled 'WN,' 'AM4', 'AM50', 'AM100', '2T', '4T', '6T', 'CF,' and 'CT' represent different contralateral noise conditions, including white noise, amplitude-modulated noise at 4 Hz, 50 Hz, and 100 Hz, 2-talker, 4-talker, and 6-talker speech babble, cafeteria noise, and traffic noise, respectively.

Columns 2 to 11 include the average amplitude of TEOAE for each condition, obtained by computing the mean of all recordings in that condition. The amplitude of TEOAE for each recording is provided separately in successive columns. The columns labeled 'BL_1', 'BL_2', and 'BL_3' include the global amplitude of TEOAE in the baseline condition for the first, second, and third recording, respectively.

The supplementary file 'TEOAE_global_suppression' includes the magnitude of suppression of TEOAE for various contralateral noise conditions. It was computed by subtracting the amplitudes of TEOAEs in each contralateral noise condition from the baseline condition.

The supplementary file 'TEOAE_band_amplitude' includes the average amplitude of TEOAE for various 2 ms duration time bands across eight time bands between 2 and 18 ms. This analysis was performed using the EchoMaster software program. Each column in the file is labeled with a suffix indicating the time band in ms.

The supplementary file 'TEOAE_band_suppression' includes the magnitude of suppression of TEOAE for various time bands across contralateral noise conditions. It was obtained by subtracting the amplitudes of TEOAEs in each contralateral noise condition from the baseline condition.

The raw data is available at doi: 10.17632/ytxmkyzgr4.1.

Overall, this dataset is valuable for understanding the role of efferent pathways in real-life situations and can be used for advanced analysis such as time-frequency analysis and wavelet analysis of TEOAEs. It is also useful for measuring intra-session reliability of TEOAEs, intra-session reliability of contralateral suppression of TEOAEs, individual variability of TEOAEs, and individual variability of contralateral suppression of TEOAEs.
collection_explanation: The dataset was collected as part of a study approved by the Institutional Ethics Committee of Kasturba Medical College, Mangalore. Informed consent was obtained from all participants before they participated in the study. The dataset consists of processed Transient Evoked Otoacoustic Emission (TEOAE) data in ".xlsx" format. The data includes the global amplitude of TEOAEs (in dB SPL), noise floor (in dB SPL), and signal-to-noise ratio (SNR) across different conditions. The data was recorded using the ILO v6 analysis software. Each participant is represented by a unique ID in the first column of the spreadsheet. The amplitude of TEOAE for baseline and various noise conditions are provided in separate columns. The data for each participant is provided in one row. The columns represent different noise conditions, such as white noise, amplitude-modulated noise at different frequencies, speech babble, cafeteria noise, and traffic noise. The average amplitude of TEOAE for each condition is provided in columns 2 to 11, with each recording's amplitude provided separately in successive columns. The dataset also includes the amplitude of TEOAE for each recording in the baseline condition, as well as for each contralateral noise condition. The dataset also includes the magnitude of suppression of TEOAE for each contralateral noise condition, which was computed by subtracting the amplitudes of TEOAEs in each noise condition from the baseline condition. Additionally, the dataset includes the average amplitude of TEOAE for various time bands between 2 and 18 ms, computed using the EchoMaster software program. The dataset also includes the magnitude of suppression of TEOAE for each time band and noise condition. The raw data is available at doi: 10.17632/ytxmkyzgr4.1.

uses_data: The collected data consists of temperature measurements in refrigerated storage. The data was acquired using i-buttons, specifically the Thermocron model. The data is stored in a Microsoft Excel worksheet. The purpose of collecting this data is to understand the typical temperature variations in vacuum packaged chilled beef in Chinese export cold supply chains. Additionally, the data can be used in beef shelf life prediction models. The data also allows for a comparison of the performance of i-buttons and LogTag temperature loggers.
collection_explanation:
The dataset was collected by measuring temperature data using i-buttons (Thermocron-TCS) and LogTags (TRIX-16). The i-buttons were used to measure temperature approximately every 25 minutes, while the LogTags measured temperature every 15 minutes throughout the storage period. The time point of each temperature reading was recorded by the data loggers. 

The experiment involved vacuum packaged Australian beef striploins (VPCB) that were stored under near ideal conditions (~-1 C) in Australia (CONTROL). The VPCB was then shipped via land and sea to three destinations in China (China-1, China-2, China-3). The cartons were stored for different durations of 84, 98, 120, and 140 days.

After the data collection period, the data from each logger were downloaded and imported into a Microsoft Excel Worksheet format for further analysis.

authoring_maintenance_policies: No, there is no mention about maintenance policies of the dataset in the context.
uses_uses:
The recommended uses of the dataset are: 
- To provide detailed knowledge on the effects of valorphins on lipid bilayers, which can be relevant to membrane-mediated mechanisms of valorphin interaction with cells and subcellular structures.
- To benefit the biophysical and pharmacological research community by providing datasets on the structural, thermodynamic, and mechanical properties of lipid membranes containing valorphins with nociceptive activity.
- To support the development of new peptide drug candidates with target specificity and pharmacokinetics tailored by amino acid or backbone modifications.
- To aid in the development of liposome-based applications, including the design of novel drug carriers.
uses_ml_approach: No, there is no mention about any test using a machine learning approach.
uses_data_limits: No, there is no mention about non-recommended uses or generalization limits of the data.
uses_represents_people: No. The data does not represent people.
uses_collected_from_people: No. The subjects of the collection process are not humans. The data collection process involved measurements and analyses of various types of vesicles and membranes.
uses_data:
The collected data in this study includes various types of measurements and analyses. The bending modulus values were calculated from data on populations of 6 to 13 giant unilamellar vesicles (GUVs) using algorithms to eliminate systematic artifacts. Fluorescence spectroscopy data were collected from 20 measurements of two different large unilamellar vesicle (LUV) preparations for each peptide investigated. Membrane capacitance values were reported based on electrodeformation data of 9 to 30 GUVs. Isothermal titration calorimetry (ITC) data were corrected by the average area of dilution peaks prior to evaluation of reaction enthalpies and binding isotherms. Electrochemical data were reported as the mean value of three independent measurements. Average vesicle sizes were calculated from multi-angle dynamic light scattering signal acquired from six independent measurements. The same number of runs was performed to obtain the electrophoretic mobility datasets.

The data is available in the Mendeley Data repository and includes fluorescence spectroscopy, ITC, voltammetry, and vesicle electrodeformation data. The value of the data lies in providing detailed knowledge on the effects of valorphins and new VV-hemorphin-5 analogues on lipid bilayer properties, which is relevant to understanding their interaction with cells and subcellular structures. The data can benefit the biophysical and pharmacological research community by providing a comprehensive picture of the structural, thermodynamic, and mechanical properties of lipid membranes containing valorphins. Additionally, the data can support the development of new peptide drug candidates with specific target specificity and pharmacokinetics. The data on valorphin analogues may also be helpful in the design of novel liposome-based drug carriers. The objective of this data contribution is to provide complementary details and support the discussion in the related research article, as well as make the data accessible for further analysis and research.
collection_explanation:
The dataset was collected through various experimental procedures. For the bending modulus data, populations of 6 to 13 giant unilamellar vesicles (GUVs) were accepted based on algorithms that eliminated systematic artifacts. These artifacts included correlated contours, volume and surface changes, non-quasisphericity, blurred contours, and membrane defects. 

Fluorescence spectroscopy data were collected from 20 measurements of two different large unilamellar vesicle (LUV) preparations for each peptide investigated. 

Membrane capacitance values were reported based on electrodeformation data of 9 to 30 GUVs. 

Isothermal titration calorimetry (ITC) data were corrected by the average area of dilution peaks before evaluation of reaction enthalpies and binding isotherms. 

Electrochemical data were reported as the mean value of three independent measurements. 

Average vesicle sizes were calculated from multi-angle dynamic light scattering signal acquired from six independent measurements. The same number of runs was performed to obtain the electrophoretic mobility datasets. 

Overall, the dataset includes raw and analyzed data from Laurdan and di-8-ANEPPS fluorescence spectroscopy, electrokinetic measurements, voltammetry, and isothermal titration calorimetry. These data were collected to study the interaction of new VV-hemorphin-5 analogues with cell membrane models and provide information on lipid membranes' structural organization, mechanical, and electrical properties.
collection_team_type: The data was collected by an internal team.
collection_team_demographic: No, there is no mention of demographic information about the team who collects the data.
collection_sources:
The data has been collected from the following sources or subjects:
- ATSF data on populations of 6 to 13 GUVs
- Fluorescence spectroscopy data from 20 measurements of two different LUV preparations
- Membrane capacitance data from electrodeformation of 9 to 30 GUVs
- ITC data corrected by the average area of dilution peaks
- Electrochemical data from three independent measurements
- Average vesicle sizes calculated from multi-angle dynamic light scattering signal
- Electrophoretic mobility datasets
collection_infrastructure:
The tools, devices, and infrastructure used during the collection process include:

1. ATSF data algorithms: Used for elimination of systematic artifacts in the bending modulus calculations of GUVs.
2. Fluorescence spectroscopy: Used to collect data on two different LUV preparations for each peptide investigated.
3. Electrodeformation: Used to collect data on membrane capacitance values of GUVs.
4. ITC data correction: Average area of dilution peaks was used to correct the ITC data on reaction enthalpies and binding isotherms.
5. Electrochemical measurements: Three independent measurements were performed to obtain the electrochemical data.
6. Multi-angle dynamic light scattering: Used to calculate average vesicle sizes from six independent measurements.
7. Electrophoretic mobility measurements: The same number of runs was performed to obtain the electrophoretic mobility datasets.

These tools, devices, and infrastructure were used to collect data on the effects of valorphins on lipid bilayers and to study their interaction with cells and subcellular structures.
annotation_explanation:
The annotation process done over the data involves the elimination of systematic artifacts and the correction of data using various algorithms and techniques. For example, the bending modulus values were calculated from data on populations of GUVs (Giant Unilamellar Vesicles) after applying algorithms to eliminate systematic artifacts. Fluorescence spectroscopy data were collected from multiple measurements of LUV (Large Unilamellar Vesicles) preparations for each peptide investigated. Membrane capacitance values were reported based on electrodeformation data of GUVs. ITC (Isothermal Titration Calorimetry) data were corrected by the average area of dilution peaks. Electrochemical data were reported as the mean value of three independent measurements. Average vesicle sizes were calculated from multi-angle dynamic light scattering signal acquired from multiple measurements. The same number of runs was performed to obtain the electrophoretic mobility datasets.

The objective of the annotation process is to provide detailed knowledge on the effects of the valorphin peptides on lipid bilayers and to support the development of new peptide drug candidates. The annotated data can be beneficial for the biophysical and pharmacological research community and can be used in the design of novel drug carriers. The data availability is provided in a repository called Mendeley Data.

uses_uses:
The recommended uses of the dataset are: 
- To evaluate the sustainability of selected technologies for recovering materials from lithium-ion batteries (LIBs) and support materials selection strategies.
- To provide data on energy consumption and emissions for different steps of LIBs recovery processes.
- To compare and integrate the parameters evaluated in the ESCAPE approach (embodied energy and carbon footprint) with Life Cycle Assessment (LCA) studies.
- To propose eco-design strategies for reducing environmental impact in LIBs recycling technologies.
- To highlight the importance of using less onerous water typologies to reduce the energy impact of the processes.

uses_data:
The collected data in this study includes information on the energy consumption and emissions associated with the recovery of materials from lithium-ion batteries (LIBs). The data was obtained by analyzing 33 different technologies for LIBs recovery, which were divided into single steps to calculate the embodied energy and carbon footprint. The data is presented in tables and figures in the document.

Table 5 provides the relative and absolute values of embodied energy and carbon footprint for the 33 LIBs recovery technologies, evaluated for 1 kg of cathode. The technologies are categorized as hydrometallurgical, pyrometallurgical, or direct recycling processes. 

Table 6 provides detailed values of embodied energy and carbon footprint for each step of the considered processes. The steps are divided into four categories: thermal treatments, mechanical treatments, chemicals, and water use. The data in this table also takes into account the use of distilled water for chemical dilution and tap water for product washing.

The collected data is used to evaluate the sustainability of the selected technologies and support the identification of the most suitable activities for material extraction from waste. The parameters evaluated in the study, embodied energy and carbon footprint, can potentially be integrated and compared with Life Cycle Assessment (LCA) studies. The data also allows for the identification of eco-design strategies to reduce environmental impact, such as managing water usage.

Overall, the collected data provides valuable information on the energy consumption and emissions associated with LIBs recovery technologies, supporting the development of sustainable and environmentally-friendly approaches for material extraction from waste.
collection_explanation:
The dataset was collected using the ESCAPE approach, which is a methodology for evaluating the sustainability of strategies to recover materials from LIBs (lithium-ion batteries). The data includes information on energy consumption and emissions for all the steps of 33 selected literature processes proposed for LIBs recovery. The data was calculated for each step of the processes, including thermal treatments, mechanical treatments, chemicals, and water use. The data was referred to 1 kg of cathode material. 

The data collection process involved analyzing 33 available technologies for LIBs recovery at the laboratory scale. Each process was divided into single steps, considering chemicals, water, thermal, and mechanical treatments. The embodied energy and carbon footprint were calculated for each step, and if possible, compared to reference materials extracted from virgin sources. The data was collected using distilled water for chemical dilution and tap water for product washing. 

The collected data provides information on the sustainability of the selected technologies and can be used to support decision-making processes for the extraction of materials from waste instead of using natural resources. The parameters evaluated in the ESCAPE approach, embodied energy, and carbon footprint, can potentially be integrated and compared with Life Cycle Assessment (LCA) studies. The data can also be used for eco-design strategies to reduce environmental impact, such as managing water usage. 

The dataset is available in Tables 5 and 6 of the document, and the original data can be accessed through Mendeley Data. The ESCAPE approach allows for the rapid evaluation of technological alternatives and supports materials selection strategies. The data reported in this paper can be used by other authors and compared with other approaches for evaluating environmental impact. Overall, the ESCAPE tool is not just a pre-screening methodology but also an eco-design strategy that can guide the decision-making process for product/technology design and redesign.

uses_uses:
The recommended uses of the dataset are: 
1. Developing algorithms for the early detection and classification of fresh and rotten fruits in the agricultural field.
2. Creating computer vision-based algorithms for recognizing and classifying fresh and rotten fruits at an early stage.
3. Constructing, training, testing, analyzing, and comparing various deep learning algorithms for recognizing fresh and rotten fruits based on different features.
4. Detecting a larger number of fruit classes and achieving better performance compared to other existing datasets.
5. Enabling farmers to produce large quantities of fruit and contribute to the national economy through early recognition of fresh and rotten fruits.

uses_data: The collected data is a dataset of fresh and rotten fruits in a hyperspectral order of images. The dataset contains a total of 3,200 original images and 12,335 augmented images. The dataset includes sixteen types of fruit classes, namely fresh apple, rotten apple, fresh banana, rotten banana, fresh orange, rotten orange, fresh grape, rotten grape, fresh guava, rotten guava, fresh jujube, rotten jujube, fresh pomegranate, rotten pomegranate, fresh strawberry, and rotten strawberry. The images were captured using a digital camera with the assistance of a domain expert from an agricultural organization. All the images have a constant width and height of 512 × 512 pixels. The dataset is available for machine-based evaluation of fruit quality on Mendeley Data.
collection_explanation: The dataset was collected from 16th to 31st March 2022. The researchers collected various varieties of fresh and rotten fruit images from different fruit shops and real fields. They used a Single-lens reflex digital camera (Nikon D5600) to capture the raw fruit images in jpg format. The fresh and rotten images of different fruits were collected separately. The types of fruits included grape, guava, jujube, pomegranate, apple, banana, orange, and strawberry. No pre-treatment of the samples was done before collecting the images. The researchers were assisted by a domain specialist from an agricultural organization in collecting all the fruit images.
collection_team_type: The data was collected by an internal team.
collection_team_demographic: No, there is no mention of demographic information about the team who collects the data.
collection_sources: The data has been collected from different fruit shops and real fields in natural weather conditions.
collection_infrastructure: The tools, devices, and infrastructure used during the collection process include a digital camera, a domain expert from an agricultural organization, and a computer vision-based algorithm. The dataset also underwent preprocessing steps such as augmentation, resizing images, splitting the dataset, generating a model, and performance analysis.
annotation_explanation:
The annotation process done over the data involves several steps. First, the dataset is augmented through random rotation, scaling, shearing, cropping, shifting, and adjustments to brightness, contrast, saturation, and hue. This augmentation process helps in increasing the amount of data available for training the deep learning model. 

Next, the images are resized to a fixed size of 512x512 pixels. This ensures that all the images have the same dimensions and can be fed into the neural network model. 

After resizing, the dataset is split into training and testing sets. This allows for the evaluation of the model's performance on unseen data. 

Finally, a deep learning model is generated and trained on the augmented and resized dataset. The performance of the model is analyzed to assess its effectiveness in recognizing and classifying fresh and rotten fruits. 

Overall, the annotation process involves preprocessing the data to enhance its quality and prepare it for training a classification model.

The recommended uses of the dataset are: 
1. To analyze and compare the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) proteome using a TMT quantitative approach.
2. To understand the pathophysiology of Human African Trypanosomiasis (HAT) by combining proteomic and bioinformatics analysis.
3. To identify proteins that are significantly differentially expressed between T. b. rhodesiense and T. b. gambiense CSF samples.

uses_data:
The collected data in this study includes proteomic data obtained from a TMT 6-plex experiment. The experimental design is graphically represented in Figure 1 of the document. Table 1 provides a demographic description of the patients investigated in the experiment. Table 2 lists the proteins that were found to be significantly differentially expressed between rhodesiense and gambiense S2 CSF. Only proteins identified with at least 2 unique peptides and a false discovery rate (FDR) of 1% were considered for quantification. The peptide count and spectral count in Table 2 correspond to the number of peptides and spectra used for the quantification, respectively.

The value of the data lies in the use of the TMT quantitative approach to characterize and compare the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) proteome. The combination of proteomic and bioinformatics analysis is useful for understanding the pathophysiology of Human African Trypanosomiasis (HAT). The quantitative proteomic analysis revealed that T. b. rhodesiense strongly activates innate immunity.

The data is publicly available through ProteomeXchange and can be accessed using the identifier PXD001082.
collection_explanation:
The dataset was collected through a collaborative effort between the Foundation for Innovative New Diagnostics (FIND), the Belgian Directorate General for Development Cooperation, and various individuals including Dr Veerle Lejon, Prof. Philippe Büscher, Dr Diuedonné Mumba Ngoyi, Dr Enock Matovu, and Prof. John Enyaru. Financial support was provided by FIND for sample collection in Uganda and by the Belgian Directorate General for Development Cooperation for sample collection in the Democratic Republic of the Congo.

The patients included in the dataset were enrolled in prospective studies conducted in the Democratic Republic of the Congo and Uganda. These studies were approved by the relevant Institutional and National Ethics Committees in the respective countries, and all participants provided written informed consent. The patients were diagnosed and staged for sleeping sickness according to the guidelines of the national sleeping sickness control programs. For this study, patients were classified as stage 2, which means they had parasites in their cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) and/or a CSF white blood cell count of 45 cells/ml, following WHO guidelines. CSF samples were collected to determine the stage of sleeping sickness and were subjected to a modified single centrifugation for parasite detection. The proteomics analyses were performed on the supernatant of this centrifugation. Importantly, all CSF samples used in this study were collected before treatment administration.

The experimental features of the dataset involved the analysis of CSF samples using quantitative proteomics. The proteins in the samples were digested with trypsin and labelled with the TMT 6-plex reagents. The labelled samples were then fractionated using off-gel electrophoresis (OGE) into 12 fractions before being subjected to LC-MS/MS analysis. All the analyses, including quantitative proteomics and data analysis, were performed in Geneva, Switzerland.
collection_team_type: The data was collected by an external team.
collection_team_demographic: No, there is no mention of demographic information about the team who collects the data.
collection_sources: The data has been collected from the Foundation for Innovative New Diagnostics (FIND), the Belgian Directorate General for Development Cooperation, Dr Veerle Lejon, Prof. Philippe Büscher, Dr Diuedonné Mumba Ngoyi, Dr Enock Matovu, Prof. John Enyaru, and the PRIDE team. The data has also been collected from HAT patients enrolled in studies in the Democratic Republic of the Congo and Uganda.
collection_infrastructure: The tools and devices used during the collection process include trypsin for protein digestion, TMT 6-plex reagents for protein labeling, off-gel electrophoresis (OGE) for fractionation, and LC-MS/MS for analysis. The infrastructure used for the collection process includes the Foundation for Innovative New Diagnostics (FIND) for financial support in sample collection in Uganda, the Belgian Directorate General for Development Cooperation for financial support in patients' sample collection in the Democratic Republic of the Congo, and the relevant Institutional and National Ethics Committees of the D.R.C., Uganda, and Belgium for approval of the studies.
annotation_explanation: The annotation process done over the data involved evaluating the experimental protein dataset in the context of HAT (sleeping sickness) pathophysiology. The quantified proteins and proteins significantly differentially expressed were then submitted to pathway analysis using IPA Ingenuity and gene ontology analysis using GO-BioCompendium. This process aimed to identify specific mechanisms associated with the two forms of sleeping sickness. The data format used for analysis was MS/MS data, and CSF samples were prepared using a modified single centrifugation method.

uses_uses: The recommended uses of the dataset are to examine the impacts of irrigation dams on the incomes and food/nutritional status of farmers, to investigate the welfare impacts of irrigation dams with and without catchment restoration practices, and to conduct holistic impact evaluations that capture ecological and socio-economic variables. The dataset may also be useful for future researchers studying the impacts of investing in irrigation dams.

uses_data:
The collected data for this study consists of three datasets. The first dataset is an estimate sheet (dam_estimates.csv) which contains the data elicited from experts. This dataset captures all the important impact parameters such as expected benefits, costs, and risks of the proposed dam. The second dataset is a correlation matrix (dam_estimates_cor.csv) that defines relationships for correlated parameters. This matrix helps to understand the interdependencies between different variables. The third dataset is a legend table (dam_legend.csv) that translates variable names into readable figure labels. This table helps in interpreting the data and understanding the meaning of different variables.

In addition to the datasets, the study also provides a simulation model script (dam_code.r) written in the R programming language. This script uses the decisionSupport package to run the simulation model. The simulation model takes the input data from the estimate sheet and uses it to simulate the impacts of the intervention. The model considers economic, ecological, and nutritional impacts of the intervention.

The data was collected through an expert knowledge elicitation approach. Experts who were knowledgeable about the dam construction and familiar with the planned intervention were selected purposively. The experts were selected from different fields of specialization to capture the detailed impact pathway of the intervention.

The collected data is valuable for the ex-ante evaluation of the irrigation dam. It provides insights into the welfare impacts of irrigation dams, both with and without catchment restoration practices. The data can be used to examine how the construction of an irrigation dam affects the incomes, as well as the food and nutritional status of farmers affected by the intervention. The data is also valuable for holistic impact evaluation that captures important ecological and socio-economic variables. It can be useful for future researchers studying the impacts of investing in irrigation dams.

The output results of the simulation are presented as spreadsheets (mcSimulationResults.csv) and graphs (contents of the 'compound figures' folder). These results provide a comprehensive understanding of the impacts of the irrigation dam intervention.
collection_explanation: The dataset was collected using an expert knowledge elicitation approach. The experts developed an impact pathway model that shows the expected costs, benefits, and risks of the proposed intervention. Before collecting the quantitative estimates, the experts were calibrated informally. The experts were selected purposively based on their knowledge about the dam construction, the construction site, and familiarity with the planned intervention. The dataset captures all the parameters considered important in the impact pathway of the decision to construct an irrigation dam. The data is disaggregated for two impact pathway models: one complementing the dam construction with catchment restoration and the other without catchment restoration. The dataset includes three.csv datasets: an estimate sheet containing the data elicited from experts, a correlation matrix defining relationships for correlated parameters, and a legend table translating variable names into readable figure labels. Additionally, the dataset includes a simulation model script written in the R programming language using the decisionSupport package. The dataset can be used to examine how the construction of an irrigation dam affects the incomes, as well as the food and nutritional status of farmers affected by the intervention.

- Expert knowledge elicitation approach: This approach was used to acquire the data by gathering information from experts who have knowledge about the dam construction and the planned intervention. The experts were selected based on their familiarity with the construction site and their specialization in different fields.

- Impact pathway model: The experts developed an impact pathway model that shows the expected costs, benefits, and risks of the proposed intervention. This model was used to guide the data collection process.

- Quantitative data collection: Quantitative data was collected based on the experts' state of understanding. The specific tools or devices used for data collection are not mentioned in the context.

The data collected captures all the parameters considered important in the impact pathway of the decision to construct an irrigation dam. The dataset is disaggregated for two impact pathway models: one complementing the dam construction with catchment restoration and the other without catchment restoration. The data can be used to examine how the construction of an irrigation dam affects the incomes as well as the food and nutritional status of farmers affected by the intervention.

uses_uses:
The recommended uses of the dataset are: 
1. Perform estimations concerning offer and demand of multimodal passenger transport in the NEC.
2. Econometric estimation of any model referring to multimodal passenger transport in the NEC.
3. Achieve an understanding of the demand and offer in the megaregions and any transport route.
4. Improve the data available for investigation to advance knowledge of transport mode and behavior of transport givers and demanders.
5. Assess the effect of maximizing business strategies and public policies for businesses and public administrations.
6. Establish quantitative criteria for measuring gains and losses for the consumer's well-being.
7. Estimate a multimodal Rotterdam demand model and cover a homogeneous period.

The data collected includes information on different modes of passenger transport, such as railway, air, car, and coach transport. The dataset includes data on the number of passengers, transport prices, and budget shares for each mode of transport.
uses_data:
The collected data in this dataset includes information on the different modes of passenger transport in the Northeast Corridor (NEC) of the United States. The data covers the period from 2003 to 2016 and includes variables such as the number of passengers, average prices, and average share of the consumers' budget for each mode of transport.

The dataset includes data on railway passenger transport, specifically the Acela and Northeast Regional services that connect cities such as Boston, Providence, New York, Philadelphia, Baltimore, and Washington DC. The data for railway transport includes the total number of annual passengers and the average annual prices of the service.

Passenger air transport data is also included in the dataset, covering routes such as New York-Washington DC, Boston-New York, Boston-Philadelphia, and Boston-Washington DC. The data for air transport includes the annual number of passengers and the average prices per route.

Data on car and coach transport is collected based on the number of vehicles per freeway. The data is selected based on annual vehicle miles traveled (AVMT) available from the statistical center of the State of Delaware and the statistical department of the State of Maryland. The primary alternative for trips between cities in the NEC is the Interstate Highway 95 (I-95). The dataset includes prices per car journey, prices of petrol and by-products, and prices per coach journey.

Statistics concerning the share of each mode of transport in the cost to the consumer can be found in Table 1100 of the Bureau of Labor Statistics (BLS).

The dataset is valuable for estimating the offer and demand of multimodal passenger transport in the NEC, as well as for econometric estimation of any model related to multimodal passenger transport. It provides insights into the preferences and behavior of transport consumers and can be used to assess the effects of business strategies and public policies.

Overall, the dataset provides comprehensive data on the number of passengers, transport prices, and budget shares for different modes of transport in the NEC, allowing for a better understanding of passenger transport demand in the region.
collection_explanation:
The dataset was collected from public agencies and repositories. The data collection process involved requesting annual data series from Table 1100 (BLS) for the years 2003-2011. The dataset includes information on the number of passengers, prices, and budget shares for different modes of passenger transport in the Northeast Corridor (NEC) of the United States. 

For railway passenger transport, data was obtained from two Amtrak services: Acela and Northeast Regional, which connect cities such as Boston, Providence, New York, Philadelphia, Baltimore, and Washington DC. The data includes the total number of annual passengers and the average annual prices of the service, weighted by the number of passengers.

For passenger air transport, data was collected for routes such as New York-Washington DC, Boston-New York, Boston-Philadelphia, and Boston-Washington DC. The data includes the annual number of passengers and the average prices per route. The data was obtained through random monthly surveys on 10% of all tickets sold in the United States.

For car and coach transport, the number of passengers was calculated based on data available on the number of vehicles per freeway. The data on annual vehicle miles traveled (AVMT) was obtained from the statistical center of the State of Delaware and the statistical department of the State of Maryland. The prices per car journey were obtained from a reference source, and the prices of petrol and by-products were obtained from another reference source. The prices per coach journey were obtained from a different reference source.

Statistics concerning the share of each mode of transport in the cost to the consumer can be found in Table 1100 of the Bureau of Labor Statistics (BLS). However, detailed tables prior to 2013 need to be requested directly from the BLS.

Overall, the data collection process involved gathering information from various sources, including public agencies, repositories, surveys, and reference sources.
collection_team_type: The data was collected by an external team.
collection_team_demographic: No, there is no mention of demographic information about the team who collects the data.
collection_sources: The data has been collected from public agencies, public repositories, Bureau of Transportation Statistics, statistical center of the State of Delaware, statistical department of the State of Maryland, and BLS (Table 1100).
collection_infrastructure:
The tools, devices, and infrastructure used during the data collection process include:

1. Public repositories: Data were collected from public agencies and their repositories.

2. Surveys: Random monthly surveys were conducted on 10% of all tickets sold in the United States for passenger air transport data.

3. Statistical data: Data on car and coach transport were collected from the statistical center of the State of Delaware and the statistical department of the State of Maryland. This data included annual vehicle miles traveled (AVMT) on Interstate Highway 95 (I-95).

4. Traffic meters: The lack of official statistics on the number of passengers and road transport prices was addressed by reconstructing the series from the NEC freeway traffic meters.

5. Calculation and estimation software: The final estimation was obtained using the R programming language and the software package "systemfit."

Overall, a combination of public data sources, surveys, statistical data, and traffic meters were used to collect the necessary data for the research.
annotation_explanation:
The annotation process done over the data involves the following steps:

1. Accessing the data: The researcher acknowledges Taylor J. Wilson, an economist from the Bureau of Labor Statistics, for helping in accessing the data.

2. Data collection: The data used in the study were obtained from public agencies and found in public repositories. The methodology used by the agencies is detailed in their repositories.

3. Adjustments to the data: Some calculations and adjustments are necessary to quantify the number of passengers per mode of transport and the prices they face each year. For car and coach transport, the AVMT series undergoes adjustments such as dividing it by the average distance of the journey per freeway in the NEC, multiplying it by the share of cars and coaches within the total amount of traffic circulation in the US, and multiplying it by the average number of passengers per vehicle. The costs per journey by cars and coaches are multiplied by the average distance of the journey in the NEC and divided by the average number of passengers per vehicle. The missing data series of prices per coach can be extrapolated from the increases expressed in the index numbers of the price series of gasoil.

4. Joint quantification of transport per road: The number of passengers is added, and a price is calculated weighted by the number of passengers of each mode.

5. Expenditure analysis: The data series in Table 1100 provide information on consumers' budget shares for various categories. The researcher distinguishes between costs per consumer for different types of trips and calculates the percentage of expenditures on out-of-town trips in relation to expenditures on the entire related set. This value is then multiplied by the different expenditures on cars.

6. Estimation and analysis: The final estimation is obtained using the R programming language and the software package "systemfit".

7. Visualization: The data series are presented in napierian logarithms in Figures 1 to 3.

The data collected includes geological maps, field photographs, microphotographs, and data tables related to the geological features and geochemistry of the Ulindakonda vent agglomerate in the Gadwal Greenstone Belt.
uses_data: The collected data in this article includes a geological map of the Gadwal Greenstone Belt, field photographs, microphotographs, a data table of major oxide and trace elements, and various geochemical plots. This data provides information on the tectonic context, petrography, and geochemistry of the trachyandesite of Ulindakonda vent agglomerate in the Gadwal Greenstone Belt. The Ulindakonda vent agglomerate reflects the features of vent agglomerate of Archean age and exhibits the geochemical characteristics of an intermediate volcanics (trachyandesite). This data can be used to gain a better understanding of the geochemical characteristics of the trachyandesite and its correlation with the generation of andesitic magmas during subduction. The data is available in its original form on Mendeley Data. The authors of the paper have contributed to the conceptualization, methodology, software, validation, analysis, investigation, data curation, writing, visualization, supervision, project administration, and funding acquisition.
collection_explanation: The dataset was collected through a series of laboratory studies and analyses. The rock samples of trachyandesite were collected from fresh outcrops, and un-weathered specimens were selected for thin section-preparation and representative samples for whole rock geochemical analysis. Petrographic studies of the rock groups were conducted using a Petrological microscope. The representative samples were powdered and subjected to major and trace element analysis using XRF and HRICP-MS techniques. Major elements were analyzed using pressed pellets on an X-Ray Florescence Spectrometer, while trace and rare earth elements were determined using High-Resolution Inductively Coupled Mass Spectrometry. The REE and trace elements data were normalized using Chondrite and Primitive mantle. The sample dissolutions were carried out in Savillex pressure decomposition containers using electronic grade HF, distilled HNO3 and HCl, and analytical reagent (AR) grade HClO4. The wet chemical approach was used to dissolve selected rock samples. Procedural blanks were also made to eliminate mistakes caused by reagent and handling. The scanning of specific ions was carried out using a Meinhard nebulizer with a cyclonic spray chamber.
